<SECOND>AM-Angola South Africa,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Both Sides Say Second Round of Talks Made Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Both sides reported progress at the second round of South Africa-Angola talks which ended Friday and said the talks would lead to further meetings soon involving the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. The governments are seeking an end to conflicts in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that include a civil war in Marxist <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and a war for independence in <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Roelof </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, said, `` I hope that what we have started would one day be rewarded with peace, stability and prosperity for the whole of southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` We are both agreed that there can be no military solution for our continent and in particular for southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' The South African delegation was exuberant and clearly considered its reception in this socialist nation a triumph. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> exchanged gifts with Foreign Minister <PERSON> Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Ndinga-Oba </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION> before leaving for home. Congolese sources said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> met privately with President <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sassou </PERSON> <PERSON> Nguesso </PERSON>, one of the continent's most vocal opponents of apartheid, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s policy of racial separation. The sources spoke on condition of anonymity. Justice Minister <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Van-Dunem </PERSON> led <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s delegation. `` We do know what each other wants and we cleared our stance,'' he said. Angolan and South African officials said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> diplomats would attend the next session of talks. Both nations attended talks last week in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> aimed at a regional peace settlement. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration seeks withdrawal of an estimated 40,000 Cuban soldiers from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> says its forces are there to help <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> fend off South African incursions. Rebels who have been fighting a guerrilla war for 13 years, seeking to overthrow the Angolan government, are supported by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>, also is fighting a bush war trying to force <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to leave <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, commonly known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, and for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to become independent. Friday's four-hour talks were held in a small, government-owned villa and ended on a cordial note with each side thanking the other for its frankness. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
