<FIRST>r w AM-MalpracticeAward     05-14 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malpractice Award,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Awards $10 Million to Brain-Damaged Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury awarded $ 10 million Friday to a <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> child who suffered irreversible brain damage during birth. The four-man, two-woman <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury decided on the award after hearing testimony that three doctors named in the case did not act quickly when tests indicated the baby's heart rate was slowing. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Olender </PERSON>, attorney for 3-year-old <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said he believed it was the largest medical malpractice award ever in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Olender </PERSON> said obstetricians <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Safran </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Horwitz </PERSON> performed an emergency caesarian section delivery about four hours after problems were first noticed. The operation was not conducted in time to prevent the child from suffering irreversible brain damage, <PERSON> Olender </PERSON> said. `` He's unable to walk, talk, or feed himself,'' said <PERSON> Olender </PERSON>. `` Everything has to be done for him.'' The judgment is about $ 6 million dollars greater than the malpractice insurance policy held by the doctors, who are in partnership. The child's parents, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> McLean </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, will receive no compensation in the award, <PERSON> Olender </PERSON> said. Instead, the money will be placed in a trust fund under court approval and used for the child's care. Attorneys for the doctors did not say whether an appeal of the verdict or award is planned. Problems in the birth arose around 4 a.m. on Dec. 11, 1984, when an electronic fetal monitor indicated that the child's heart rate was slowing, <PERSON> Olender </PERSON> told the court. In such cases, a declining heart rate often indicates a shortage of oxygen, usually resulting from a pinching of the umbilical cord, and emergency caesarian section deliveries are usually performed as soon as the problem is discovered, <PERSON> Olender </PERSON> asserted. The emergency operation did not take place until 9:15 a.m. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> hospital where the birth took place _ originally was named in the suit, but was dropped from the case when it agreed to pay $ 800,000 in a settlement.
</TEXT>
