<FIRST>r i AM-Publisher-Holocaust     05-14 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Publisher-Holocaust,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Gets Nine-Month Sentence For Printing Statements Denying
Holocaust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A publisher convicted in a retrial of maliciously publishing statements denying the Holocaust was sentenced Friday to nine months in jail. <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> Zundel </PERSON>, 49, arrived at the district courthouse bearing a small coffin inscribed with the words `` Free Speech is Dead.'' After his 1985 conviction he went to his sentencing carring a heavy wooden cross, also signifying the demise of freedom of speech in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. As in his earlier conviction, <PERSON> Zundel </PERSON> is seeking to appeal his sentence and jury conviction and has applied for bail to keep him out of jail at least until his appeal can be considered. But he had to start the weekend behind bars awaiting a bail decision. The West German immigrant won his first appeal and was granted a new trial in district court that ended in the second conviction. <PERSON> Zundel </PERSON>, who operates <ORGANIZATION> Samisdat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, was charged under a law forbidding publication of statements known to be false or likely to cause injury or mischief to the public interest. <PERSON> Zundel </PERSON> was charged with publishing a booklet _ which he did not write _ that denies official accounts of Nazis exterminating Jews in wartime prison camps. The booklet says the horror stories about the Holocaust were all a hoax and a fraudulent scheme by Zionists to extract financial reparation from postwar <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. However, Judge <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> took judicial notice of the Holocaust at the beginning of the trial, recognizing it as a historical fact. From then on, <PERSON> Zundel </PERSON>'s essential defense was that he honestly believed the contents of the pamphlet and was not knowingly spreading false news, as the charge alleged. Jewish leaders were happy with the verdict, saying it would serve to protect ethnic minorities from social intolerance. The Canadian Jewish <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> said it `` demonstrates that Canadians will not tolerate the vilification of ethnological communities. `` It reaffirms the effectiveness of the Criminal Code in upholding social and racial harmony,'' group officials said. B'nai B'rith <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> expressed confidence the outcome `` will serve to deter hatemongers, no matter who their targets may be, from pursuing their aim of dividing Canadian society and turning some of us against our fellow citizens.''
</TEXT>
