<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Education, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0798,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC and Teachers Open Conference on AIDS Education</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to ADD NEA membership; PICKS UP 4th
graf pvs, `The role ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> launched their first joint conference on AIDS and education Friday with a focus on showing teachers how to teach about the deadly disease. The three-day conference, expected to draw 100 educators from around the country, is the latest event in what <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> described as her association's `` all-out war against AIDS.'' `` We are going to work with our members to determine what we can do as an organization to raise the consciousness level of the members of our profession,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Futtrell </PERSON>. The NEA is the nation's largest teacher union, with 1.9 million members. `` The role of a teacher is a especially critical in dealing with young people,'' she said. `` Children trust their teachers and they will go to their teachers for information. We must have factual information and know how to respond to young people.'' Ms. <PERSON> Futrell </PERSON> added she hopes the conference will spur action on AIDS education. `` We do n't think we can wait five years,'' she said. `` We need to begin to talk to young people now about changing their behavior so they do n't get the disease.'' Friday's keynote speaker was <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Washburn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, an AIDS patient who is retired superintendent of the <ORGANIZATION> Brighton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` We've got a mission,'' <PERSON> Washburn </PERSON> said in an interview before his address. `` The kids in our high schools are going to bear the brunt of this disease and they're going to bear the cost.'' <PERSON> Washburn </PERSON>, 48, was diagnosed last spring with AIDS and disclosed his illness in January, when he embarked on a series of appearances and speeches to educate high school and college students and teachers about the disease. `` Exploit me,'' said <PERSON> Washburn </PERSON>. `` My time is limited. I want to be exploited by whoever can use me to put windows on what is now happening with AIDS and what is likely to happen. `` My years in public school work have groomed me. ... I'm not embarrassed by the questions,'' said <PERSON> Washburn </PERSON>, who is homosexual. Other participants in the conference include researchers and officials of the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. Discussion will include ways to incorporate AIDS education into the school curriculum. The <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s parent agency, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, are members of the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, created in 1987 in an AIDS education effort. Last fall, the network distributed 1.9 million copies of a handbook for teachers on AIDS. AIDS has struck 973 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> children under age 13; of those, 566 have died, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. In all, AIDS has struck more than 61,000 people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, killing more than 34,000 of them.
</TEXT>
