 A judge ordered actor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON> to return his 5-year-old son to a former girlfriend by Tuesday or face fines and possible arrest. <ORGANIZATION> Monmouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehrer </PERSON> issued the order Friday after <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> <PERSON> Felder </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sommerville </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON>, requested an arrest order because <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON> had not returned his son, <PERSON> Lorcan </PERSON>, by a May 7 deadline. <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON> and his former girlfriend, a <LOCATION> Navesink </LOCATION> resident who has taken the 55-year-old actor's name but never married him, have joint custody of the boy. Last December, they agreed to switch custody of <PERSON> Lorcan </PERSON> every three months until September 1989, when they hope to reach a long-term agreement. <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON> took <PERSON> Lorcan </PERSON> to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in February. His attorney, <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON>, said <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON> held on to the boy because Ms. <PERSON> Somerville </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON> violated the custody agreement by firing <PERSON> Lorcan </PERSON>'s nanny. `` <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> was acting ... in the interests of <PERSON> Lorcan </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lehrer </PERSON> scheduled a hearing on the custody case for June 14. <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON> faces $ 1,000 a day in fines if he does not comply with the order, <PERSON> Felder </PERSON> and <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said.
