<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actor-director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> has been keeping busy during his journey to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. On Friday, he announced that Soviet scientists would attend a conference on ecology this fall at the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sundance </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, which he founded. He also said two Soviet movie makers would visit his <ORGANIZATION> Sundance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Filmmakers </ORGANIZATION> next year to meet with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> counterparts. <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> said the agreements resulted from meetings in the past four days with prominent members of both professions. <PERSON> Redford </PERSON>, long active as an environmentalist, also moderated a two-day conference on depletion of the ozone layer in the upper atmosphere. Not everything, however, was conducted over a conference table. <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> presided over the showing of eight of his movies in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He was scheduled to put on more showings in <LOCATION> Tiblisi </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, today and Sunday.
