Goldfish cracker in July 1986 that she said contained an aspirin-substitute pill. The matter was settled out of court for $ 500, less than two months prior to Ms. <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON>'s selection for Mrs. <PERSON> Nickell </PERSON>'s jury. Ms. <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON> told <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> she dismissed the anonymous call from her mind and judged the case on the facts. She also said she did not mention her own lawsuit during jury selection because she did not think it was relevant. Ms. <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON> also said Friday that during the trial, she had talked with friends about writing an article about her jury experiences, but did not discuss facts of the case. After the unusual session Friday, defense lawyer <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> said he would file a mistrial motion within a week. `` The testimony of juror <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON> raised very serious and troubling questions on her ability to sit on this jury,'' <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON>'s failure to reveal her own suit kept lawyers from questioning her about that fact, <PERSON> Hillier </PERSON> said. Further, he said there was no way to verify her statements that the phone call had no effect on her decision. Federal prosecutor <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Maida </PERSON> declined to comment.
