<DATELINE>AGUASCALIENTES, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers were called out Friday to help dig for people missing in the rubble of a building collapse that killed at least 13 the day before. Red Cross and state government officials confirmed the number known dead and said 53 people were injured. <PERSON> Gilberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, radio officer at police headquarters, said about 60 soldiers from the army garrison joined firefighters, police and volunteers in the rescue effort. Bulldozers and cranes were brought from as far away as <LOCATION> Salamanca </LOCATION>, 78 miles to the southwest. <LOCATION> Aguascalientes </LOCATION>, a city of about 500,000 people 320 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, is the capital of <LOCATION> Aguascalientes </LOCATION> state. By late Friday, two or three people were believed still trapped in the rubble, <PERSON> Celia </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Torre </PERSON>, a state government spokeswoman said. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, head of special services for the local <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, said hundreds of people came to help in the rescue. At least 116 workers were in the building when the four upper stories collapsed, said <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, reached by telephone from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` Relatives of the victims practically attacked the ambulances, trying to identify'' the victims, he said. The building, still under construction, consisted of three basements, a main floor and three upper stories. As workers were about to pour the last concrete late Thursday afternoon, it collapsed onto a furniture factory that occupied the ground floor and part of the basement area. Lower floors of buildings in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> often are occupied while the upper stories are constructed. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Aguascalientes </LOC