<FIRST>r a PM-Business-Trade Bjt   05-14 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business-Trade, Bjt,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Bill Likely To Survive Veto, Business Leaders Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business leaders and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials are betting that <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have worked too hard to fashion trade legislation to scuttle it after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s expected veto. `` Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have put a great deal of work in this legislation and my judgment is that these persons will not wish to see the bill disappear,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said Friday. `` They have a great deal of time, effort, energy and creativity invested in this piece of legislation.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said he expected the president to deliver his veto message to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> next week, but he said he was optimistic about it not meaning the end of the three-year effort to write the trade bill. Although not specifically mentioning <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, by name, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> noted that a provision repealing the windfall oil profits tax is dear to the hearts of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> legislators. `` I suspect it will be particularly difficult for them to explain to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> constituents that they were willing to drop a piece of legislation so important to the state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> spoke with reporters after addressing a private session of the Business Council. Composed of 61 chief executives of the nation's largest corporations, the council meets twice a year at the Homestead, a posh resort in the mountains of southwestern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is vetoing the massive trade bill because of a provision that would require companies to give 60 days' notice of plant closings and major layoffs. The administration supports much of the 1,000-page bill, but objects to the plant-closing provision, which <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> called `` onerous.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said the technical language of the provision would provide `` a field day for lawyers and a nightmare for American businessmen'' by providing a legal basis for challenging virtually every plant closing or layoff. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, one of the executives attending the retreat ending today, acknowledged that a veto of the trade bill risked losing `` very constructive'' legislation, but he said, `` The business community is prepared to take that risk. `` It's been called simple plant-closing legislation, well it's 10 sections and 56 subsections and inconsistent language,'' he said The business executives, in an economic report issued at the start of their conference, predicted that last year's record trade deficit of $ 171.2 billion would drop below $ 150 billion this year. But, the forecast, which reflects a consensus of the member companies' chief economists, said the reduction would not be enough to stem the fall of the dollar. It said the dollar, which has lost about half of its value against the Japanese yen in two years, would fall from its present level of 125 yen to about 115 yen by the end of 1989. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest bank holding company, said a substantial improvement in the trade deficit was iminent because of the devalued dollar. A weaker dollar improves <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export prospects by lower the cost of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods overseas. `` There is a price at which the trade balance will turn around, and most of us think we're pretty close to it,'' <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> said. Generally, the executives' forecast painted a rosy picture of moderate economic growth, manageable inflation and low unemployment. It said growth, as measured by the gross national product, would be 2.4 percent this year, down from 3.8 percent last year. Inflation of consumer prices was expected to be 3.9 percent this year, down from 4.4 percent in 1987. Unemployment, now at 5.4 percent, should remain under 6 percent through 1989, the executives said.
