<HEAD>State to Drop Controls Over Art Troupes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is lifting controls on most art troupes and will let individuals organize their own performing groups, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The daily quoted Culture Minister <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Meng </PERSON> as saying state-run art troupes will be replaced with a system that will permit free and open competition among troupes. Performers will be allowed to set their own box office prices and decide their own programs as long as they are licensed and do not violate state laws and regulations. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said the reforms are designed to stimulate the professional enthusiam of the 200,000 people working in the nation's 3,094 art troupes. He said many state-run troupes, where lifetime employment prevails, are overstaffed, especially with those who are old and in poor health. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said the state will continue to run a small number of the country's best troupes or those needing special state support. Among those are new experimental groups and groups in ethnic minority areas. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> said state-run troupes will also adopt a new salary system with outstanding performers receiving better pay than those with mediocre skills or past their prime. The state's decision to give up its monopoly over the arts has drawn some criticism in the official press, with artists being quoted as saying many traditional Chinese and minority musical, dance and opera troupes are doomed by the `` survival of the fittest'' policy. Concern has also been raised that troupes forced to pay their own way will turn to sex, violence and superstition to draw audiences.
