<HEAD>ICC Tentatively Votes To Approve Union Pacific Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposed purchase of the regional <ORGANIZATION> Missouri-Kansas-Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been tentatively approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, sources say. The regulatory agency has scheduled an official announcement on Monday of its decision. Agency and congressional sources, speaking on condition they not be identified, said the commission had voted 4-0 on Friday to permit the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> and MKT merger. The Union Pacific, a 21,500-mile network, proposed in November 1986 to acquire the 3,100-mile MKT system, known as the Katy line, for $ 110 million and to assume its outstanding debts. As proposed, the merger would eliminate about 1,100 <PERSON> Katy </PERSON> jobs because of closing of rail yards and repair shops. <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> also proposed the abandonment of 405 miles of track, mostly operated by <PERSON> Katy </PERSON>. The Union Pacific, the nation's third largest railroad system in terms of track mileage, serves about 20 states with routes from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in the West to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The company was formed in 1982 with the merger of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> railroads. The Katy serves six states, with mostly north-south routes running from <LOCATION> Omaha