<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb exploded inside a truck early Saturday near reviewing stands being prepared for farewell ceremonies marking the Soviet withdrawal. Police said eight people were killed and 20 injured. The blast occurred at 5:45 a.m. -LRB- 9:15 p.m. EDT -RRB- in a housing area on the banks of the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Witnesses said they saw four bodies being removed from a house that was destroyed. The blast demolished embankment walls on both sides of the river that threads through the Afghan capital. Blood was visible on the gates of a nearby factory and personal belongings, including carpet slippers, were scattered in the street. Witnesses said flames were visible when they arrived shortly after the blast. The bomb had been planted in a large truck that lay badly mangled at the scene. Last month, six people were killed and 49 wounded in another bomb blast along the river banks on the 10th anniversary of the April 1978 revolution that brought a Marxist government to power in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and triggered widespread insurrection. Soviet soldiers entered the war in December 1979 to help the allied government fight off the anti-Communist rebels. About 115,000 remain here to back forces loyal to President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. But under an accord signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on April 14, the Soviet troops begin pulling out Sunday and are to complete the withdrawal within nine months. Information for this account was based on a news agency pool report from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> was not allowed to go on the trip to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> because of questions it asked <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> in the capital last month.
