<HEAD>Grills Fire Up For Barbecue Cookoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Clouds of smoke rose over the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> bluffs as competitors fired up their cookers for <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>' annual barbecue contest, a weekend party of pork and beer billed as the largest shindig of its kind `` If you do him right, it'll take 24 hours,'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said Friday as he opened the side of his black iron cooker to proudly display a 135-pound pig being turned into a tender treat. `` We'll serve him with a spoon, not a knife,'' <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> added. The cook-off, part of the city's annual Memphis In May Festival, drew 175 cooking teams from around the country to compete in three categories: whole hog, ribs and pork shoulder. Judging was set for this afternoon, and the winners were to be announced tonight. Many of the teams, varying from three or four members to dozens, also took part in a showmanship contest Friday. They staged skits in costume outside their cooking booths, which ranged from simple tents to elaborate two-story affairs and fully equipped kitchens mounted on trailers. Barbecue cookers included plain iron drums and fancy customized rigs. One team prepared its pork in a large metal cooker shaped like a rabbit. Another relied on a bright red compact car gutted and lined with iron to fashion a cooker. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, who owns a marine engine business in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, cooked his team's barbecue in what was once a 900-horsepower diesel engine. Mounted on a 20-foot-long trailer with a built-in kitchen, the shiny steel-and-iron rig cost about $ 20,000, <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. `` We're ecologically sound. We catch our own waste and we're totally self-contained,'' he said `` When we get there, we're there We've got water. We've got electricity. Just add pork and stir.'' The contest is for pork cookers only, and <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Bollheimer </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the 11-year-old event, said organizers were trying for a world record for the amount of pork barbecue served in a single day. The cook-off is billed as a `` world championship,'' but organizers were trying for the first time to take a formal accounting of the amount of meat cooked by the competitors. They predicted the total would be in the tons. `` We've heard rumors that other contests are trying to claim title as the largest, but we do n't think they have a chance,'' Ms. <PERSON> Bollheimer </PERSON> said. `` We will bask in the glory of knowing we're the world's largest barbecue contest.'' The Memphis In May Festival focuses on a different country each year, and this year's guest was <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, leading to numerous Union Jacks and other British decorations at barbecue booths. One team, the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kilted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kookers </ORGANIZATION>, included several members from <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, even though their background as barbecue cookers was limited. <PERSON> Tam </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> said it was his first brush with American barbecue. `` I tasted the ribs for the first time last night,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. `` I found some meat on the bones and it was great. The only ribs I'd had before were from a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> restaurant.''
