<HEAD>After 27 Years, Zoo Atlanta's Famous Gorilla Walks Outside</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 He was skeptical at first, a little suspicious, not sure what to make of grass, or trees, or sunshine. After all, he had n't seen those things in 27 years, since he was 3 years old. But <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON>, Zoo <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s star attraction, quickly grew on Friday to like his new home _ a $ 4.5 million outdoor `` rain forest'' where, finally, he will live like the Western lowland gorilla he is. As several dozen reporters, photographers and zoo staffers watched from behind trees and bushes and across protective moats, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> played his part perfectly at what was a coming-out _ both for him and for the once-beleaguered zoo where he lives. Just four years ago the zoo was declared one of the worst in the nation by the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Friday morning, as only a few zoo employees quietly watched, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> stepped out of his bad-weather shelter, walked around, felt rain, and ran back in. `` A very intelligent thing to do,'' pronounced a proud Zoo Atlanta Director <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Maple </PERSON>. Later, the door again was thrown open, and the great ape hopped out to meet his public. A minute later, he climbed back in. Another minute later, out again. Six minutes after that, a car horn sounded _ and he scampered back inside. All the while, his eyes darted back and forth, alert to the slightest movement or sound. But after 40 minutes, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> boldly climbed a small hill outside his door and picked up a few pieces of fruit thrown by his keeper. He heard peacocks, zoo construction trucks, an airplane, and car horns. And for the first time in 27 years, he felt the sunshine on his back. Within an hour, he was jumping in the air, trying to de-limb his first tree. The zoo director beamed. `` This is a very special moment,'' Maple said. `` I will always treasure this time. ... I'm delighted with the way he responded to the whole thing. It just could n't have been better.'' <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON>, named for former long-time <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartsfield </PERSON>, last month was moved from his tile-walled, steel-barred cage _ his home since he arrived at the zoo in May 1961 _ into the new indoor quarters he will use for sleep and shelter. After five weeks to grow accustomed to the enclosure, with <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, his keeper of 14 years, often sleeping nearby to keep him company, zoo officials decided he was ready. Soon, he will live near _ but separated from _ 13 gorillas on loan from <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Yerkes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Primate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Zoo officials hope that within a year, <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> can go on a date. `` We'll get a young, reproductive-proven female, hopefully one who could be seductive and friendly,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Yerkes </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>. `` A <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> of gorillas, to show him what to do.''
