<HEAD>Art Institute to Run Ad Apologizing for Mayor-in-Lingerie Painting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> has purchased full-page newspaper ads apologizing for a student's painting of the late Mayor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> in frilly women's underwear. The painting, titled `` Mirth and Girth,'' was seized by a group of black aldermen last week who stormed the school's halls and was later confiscated by police. While the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> prepared its apology, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> threatened a lawsuit on artist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s behalf, and discord over the black aldermen's seizure of the painting led to angry words exchanged in the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and its school _ where the painting was shown briefly in a private, juried student show _ plan to run full-page advertisements in three daily Chicago-area newspapers offering an apology for the caricature of the city's first black mayor, who died of a heart attack in November. `` It contains an apology for the distress and concern that the painting caused to the community,'' <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Harakal </PERSON> said of the ad, which will run in Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION>, and in Monday editions of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defender </ORGANIZATION>, which has a primarily black readership. `` We would like to see calm in the community,'' she said Friday. `` We never intended for there to be any unrest in the first place and want to put the entire incident behind us and move on.'' Ms. <PERSON> Harakal </PERSON> refused to release the text of the ad before publication. The <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and its school came under fire Wednesday, when aldermen began receiving telephone complaints about the work by <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> passed a resolution cutting off city funds for a school program unless the painting was removed and demanded an apology. The black aldermen then stormed the school and removed the painting. The painting was returned to <LOCATION> Nelson </LOCATION> Thursday, defaced with a 5-inch gash on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s left shoulder, after the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> intervened with the city corporation counsel, said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director. The organization is considering a lawsuit seeking monetary damages from police for violating the artist's civil rights, he said. Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, who succeeded <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said he was disgusted by the work. `` It should never have been hung. In fact, it should never have been painted.'' Several white aldermen complained Friday that black colleagues had overreacted. `` The whole thing could have been resolved with a phone call,'' said <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>. `` Now, by going to the council floor and grandstanding on the issue, millions of people will have seen this sad, insensitive, disgusting picture, as opposed to a few dozen.'' But at a meeting of black ministers Friday, the Rev. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON>, executive director of Operation PUSH, the civil rights group founded by Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, described the painting as `` the latest in a series of escalating attacks and insults against the black community.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, received dozens of calls Friday from people supporting an artist's right to show his work, Ms. <PERSON> Harakal </PERSON> said. Students said they had consulted attorneys about filing a civil rights lawsuit against the aldermen and police for impounding the painting.
