<HEAD>UAW: Contracts Stand As-is Despite Skilled Trades Rejection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>' contracts with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will stand despite a narrow rejection by skilled trades workers of a pact ratified by a majority of 66,000 union members, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> leaders say. `` The International Executive Board after reviewing all the issues ... has determined that this contract stands properly ratified,'' the union said Friday in a statement attributed to <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>. The contract was ratified by 54 percent of the vote Wednesday. Skilled trades workers, who have an additional, separate contract but cast a single vote for or against both pacts, narrowly rejected it. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> says it has about 10,500 active skilled trades workers. Delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s 140-member national <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> council who represent skilled trades workers met in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Friday with <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> and other union leaders to determine whether negotiations should resume. The union and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> could have returned to the bargaining table to discuss skilled trades issues if those had been behind the rejection. However, if the rejection was on issues in the main contract, such as economics, then the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> would take no further action. The union's decision indicated that the rejection concerned the main contract. Union officials had said before the meeting that they believed the rejection was economic, and blamed it on a $ 1,000 signing bonus. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers received a $ 2,120 bonus in 1985 for signing a three-year contract. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> executive board, which includes <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>, other <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> vice presidents and regional directors, decided to ratify the contract after receiving a report on the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> meeting. The contracts, reached May 5 after 2 -LCB- weeks of early negotiations, cover 66,000 hourly and salaried <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers in 15 states.
