<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Near Soviet Retreat Route, Killing 11</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details of explosion from photographer
on the scene, that all casualties Afghan. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KAB1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb exploded inside a truck today near reviewing stands being prepared for farewell ceremonies to mark the retreat of Soviet soldiers. Eleven Afghans were killed and 12 reported wounded. The blast occurred in the heart of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> at 5:45 a.m. -LRB- 9:15 p.m. EDT Friday -RRB- in a housing area on the banks of the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. A Western photographer on the scene told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that a baby and 11-year-old girl were among those killed and all the casualties were Afghan civilians. Most appeared to have been occupants of nearby homes destroyed by the impact of the explosion, he said. `` When the bomb exploded some of the houses nearby just collapsed.'' Witnesses said they saw four bodies being removed from one house. The blast was so great that it shattered the windows of a bus depot across the river, 300 yards away and left a crater 20 feet wide and 10 feet deep. Soviet troops arrived afterward, the photographer said by telephone. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevruk </PERSON>, deputy chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s propaganda department, also provided casualty figures to foreign reporters covering the pullout, which is to begin Sunday. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported that the blast killed 11 people and wounded 13 and blamed `` Afghan anti-government formations.'' The explosion demolished embankment walls on both sides of the river, which threads through this ancient capital city, whose streets are now filled with Soviet troops, tanks and armored personnel carriers. Blood was visible on the gates of a nearby factory and personal belongings, including carpet slippers, were scattered in the street. Witnesses said flames were visible when they arrived shortly after the blast. The bomb had been planted in a large truck that was badly mangled. Last month, six people were killed and 49 wounded in another bomb blast along the river banks on the 10th anniversary of the April 1978 revolution that brought a Marxist government to power and triggered widespread insurrection. Anti-Communist guerrillas also were blamed for a May 4 attack on a Soviet convoy north of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> that killed a photographer for the Soviet newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> and an undisclosed number of soldiers. It also wounded <PERSON> Sevruk </PERSON>'s son, who also works for <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to help the Soviet-allied government put down the insurrection. About 115,000 Soviets have been assisting <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s troops, but they will begin leaving the country on Sunday in observance of a peace agreement signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on April 14. Half of the Soviets must be out by Aug. 15, and the rest are expected to follow quickly, although the accord gives them nine months to complete the pullout. At a new conference today, the head of the Soviet military contingent in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> said the guerrilas were taking their toll on Soviet and Afghan troops, but that rebel attacks would not deter the withdrawal. `` The opposition may have some effect on us, but not much, and certainly they will not be able to frustrate the timetable,'' Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON> told reporters. Troops manning the Soviet armor in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> have been setting out gasoline pumps and supplies along the route of retreat. For security reasons, Soviet officials have been tight-lipped about the exact number of troops who will begin the move north on Sunday. The Soviet national news program Vremya reported Friday night that soldiers were ready for the withdrawal, but gave no figures. Vremya reported that 167 Soviet encampments would be left behind for the Afghans to use, but that some of the facilities would be put to civilian use as hospitals and schools. Information for this account was based in part on a news agency pool report from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> and on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> monitoring of Soviet news broadcasts. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> was not allowed to go on the trip to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> because of questions it asked <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> in the capital last month.
