<HEAD>South Korean Police Clash with Reunification Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Student protesters today hurled rocks and firebombs as police set off barrages of tear gas to break up a march advocating reunification talks with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. There were no immediate reports of arrests or injuries. The march broke off from a rally of about 10,000 students from universities around the country who gathered at <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Some prominent dissident leaders, including the Rev. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ik-hwan </PERSON>, attended the rally. Relatives of hundreds of jailed dissidents also participated. The students, many wearing headbands reading `` unification,'' also asked the government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo to make concessions to persuade <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to join the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Olympic Games in the fall. In a separate statement, the demonstrators proposed that student leaders of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> meet on June 10 to discuss national unification and the Olympic co-hosting. Unification of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> has emerged as a major campus issue as radical students shifted their anti-government strategy after legislative elections last month, when the opposition made a strong showing. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has said it would boycott the Olympics in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> unless it is allowed to co-host the Games. After the campus rally, about 5,000 students walked out of the school to begin what they called `` a grand peace march'' to headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> in downtown <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. When the marchers went 1,000 yards, about 2,000 riot police intervened, pushing the students to