<HEAD>Jazz Trumpeter Chet Baker Dies In Fall From Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with police saying Baker used heroin
before death. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American trumpeter <PERSON> Chet </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a jazz virtuoso who found fame in the 1950s but whose career was haunted by heroin addiction, died in a fall from the second floor of his hotel. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, who was 59, took heroin just before he fell from the hotel window shortly after 3:10 a.m. Friday, police spokesman <PERSON> Klaas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilting </PERSON> said today. Authorities found <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> dead in the street. Wilting said suicide was possible. But <ORGANIZATION> Ria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wigt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wigt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Productions </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s worldwide agent, said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> `` was n't the type of man'' who would commit suicide. Born <PERSON> Chesney </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Yale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, in 1929, the musician set the standard for what jazz buffs knew as the `` cool school.'' In 1952, he was working with <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> when he joined the piano-less quartet of British saxophonist <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulligan </PERSON>. With his good looks and youth and fragile, introverted tone, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> soon became a cult figure. In 1953, he topped the Metronome trumpet poll and started his own quartet. His work became more assured and outgoing. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> looked something like actor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> and sounded something like famed jazz trumpeter <PERSON> Bix </PERSON> <PERSON> Beiderbecke </PERSON>. As a player, <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> was his main inspiration. In 1955, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> took a group to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that showed high promise. Then his career started to suffer. An Italian court sentenced him to a 16-month prison term in 1960 for drug possession. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> in 1968, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said he was beaten up by hoodlums and suffered severe injuries that included the loss of his teeth, a trumpet player's nightmare. For two years <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> did n't play, but he said recently he had quit drugs. He began recording again and made an album with pop star <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>. In 1974, critic <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> wrote in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> had developed `` more range and assertiveness within the wistfully ruminative style with which he has also been associated.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> had scheduled several appearances in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> as part of a tour that also included <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. He had been staying at the <PERSON> Prins </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrik </PERSON> hotel close to <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>'s drug district, said Wilting. `` The way it looks, he had just been using'' heroin, Wilting told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Traces of heroin use were found in <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s hotel room, he added. `` Maybe he started acting funny,'' said Wilting. `` He was alone and shoved the window open himself and either fell or jumped out _ I do n't suppose we'll ever find out which.'' A receptionist at the hotel, where <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> checked in Thursday, said the musician `` was a little nervous'' when he arrived. He did not elaborate. The receptionist, who refused to give his name, said the window of <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s room slides open vertically, leaving a 10-inch gap at m