 to reply, and radios afterward were silent, the sources said. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> had monitored a radio message from an Iranian F-4 Phantom jet `` requesting permission to attack a ship.'' There was no American vessel in the area at the time, and there was no indication of what ship was referred to, the source said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships are now permitted to intervene on request in attacks on neutral shipping as well as to provide `` humanitarian aid'' to non-U.S. flag vessels, but only in international waters. Today's attack occurred inside <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s territorial waters. The Iraqis have recently intensifed air raids on tankers plying Iranian waters as part of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>'s bid to throttle the vital oil exports that help <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> finance the 7 -LCB- - year-old war The <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> High Command has claimed nine air raids on `` large maritime targets,'' meaning ships, off <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s coast in the past two weeks. Three have been confirmed by <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION>. Iraqi attacks mainly are directed at tankers in Iranian waters closer to <LOCATION> Kharg </LOCATION>, and sometimes off <LOCATION> Lavan </LOCATION> island, a terminal in the central gulf. Iraqi air forays against <PERSON> Larak </PERSON>, which would necessitate midair refueling of the jets, are rare.
