<HEAD>World's Smallest Nuclear Sub Launched</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHERBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> on Saturday launched the world's smallest nuclear-powered attack submarine Canadian government and military officials joined French dignitaries to watch the launching of the Amethyste, which will be operational in 1991. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is considering buying the submarine. The manufacturers, <ORGANIZATION> Cherbourg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION>, said it is the world's smallest nuclear-powered vessel It is 243 feet long and 23 feet wide and weighs 2,400 tons. The Amethyste has a speed of at least 25 mph and can operate at depths up to 984 feet. It carries a crew of 66. The manufacturers said the submarine carries torpedoes and anti-ship Exocet missiles. The Canadians have said they plan to use submarines of this type to patrol vast areas in the Arctic.
