<HEAD>South Looms As Tough Battleground For Democratic Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The South, once solidly Democratic in presidential races but now reliably Republican, is a tough battleground for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as he tries to put together an electoral coalition to defeat <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and enable the party to recapture the White House. With many states in the politically conservative region viewed as beyond his reach in November, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is being urged to choose a running mate who could help the Democrats carry <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the two largest states south of the Mason-Dixon line. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primaries in both those states on Super Tuesday, a fact that gives Democrats reason for optimism. Supporters of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor also are quick to argue that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does not have the hold on Southern voters that <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> could claim. It's possible for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to find the 270-vote <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> majority outside the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, a coalition that would require every big industrial state in the North plus <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and Farm Belt states where economic hard times the past seven years have made the Reagan-Bush administration politically unpopular. But any <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> strategy without the South would require an electoral shift of historic proportions for a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> victory in November. `` They can not let us sweep it -LRB- the South -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> <PERSON> Breglio </PERSON>, a Republican consultant and authority on electoral college strategies. `` If we take <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and the rest of the cotton <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, I do n't think they can win.'' `` What I ca n't figure out is how you get the numbers if you do n't run strong in the South,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, the 1984 Democratic presidential nominee. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, who served President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> political director, predicted that the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> would `` decide the South is a mirage and that their best hope lies in a sweep of the industrial belt.'' <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>, a political scientist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>, said that if the political trends go in <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' direction and he is headed for a big victory he would run well in the South, but `` if it's a close election, I'd say he has very little hope of carrying much outside of perhaps a couple of border states. For generations, 16 Southern and border states gave Democratic presidential candidates a solid electoral base. In 1944, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> took all 167 electoral votes from those states. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> broke the Democratic hold on the region in 1952 and 1956. And in 1964, when Democrat <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> crushed Sen. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>, the only bright spot for the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> was the Deep South. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> resisted the <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> landslide and backed <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON>, the only states outside of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> to support him. Since then, Southern and border states have voted strongly Republican except in 1976, when <PERSON> Georgian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> was the Democratic candidate. In 1980, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took 138 of the region's 169 electoral votes and four years later, the Republican president received all but the 3 electoral votes of the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Democratic pollster <PERSON> Natalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is based in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and she pointed out that in 1984, <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> got 13 percent of the white vote in the state. `` If the white vote tripled and the black vote came out the way it was supposed to, then <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would beat <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by half a percentage point,'' she said. `` Think about that as a mission. We've got to triple what we did in'84.'' When <PERSON> Claibourne </PERSON> <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>, an Atlanta-based pollster, was asked how <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was playing in the South, he replied, `` He does n't play so hot. He is your classical, party activist, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate for president of which we've seen many come and all go.'' There was little agreement on whether <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> would offer the best hope for a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> breakthrough. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> is where <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> makes his home, where he first became active in politics and where he was elected to a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat. A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat, who insisted on anonymity, called it `` highly unlikely'' that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> could carry the state, `` as unlikely that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would carry <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> in'84.'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Quackenbush </PERSON>, who was southern coordinator for the <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> campaign, said he thought <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had a better chance of carrying <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> than of winning <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> is just a hard state for a Democrat to take,'' he said. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Democrats talked optimistically about <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' prospects against <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in their state. `` The decision on the vice presidency will be fundamental,'' said <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, a professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Stetson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Deland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> activist. If <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> chooses Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> or Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, `` The ticket will be very saleable in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettigrew </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairman in <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> or Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> or Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> would be the strongest running mates for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> because they would `` assure people'' on foreign and defense policy. <PERSON> Pettigrew </PERSON> and <PERSON> Quackenbush </PERSON> said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> would be a lot more effective in the South than <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> took the opposite view. He said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> might not get <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> any state other than <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. While the senator could add a couple of points to the ticket in other Southern states, it might not be enough to carry any of them. `` <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> would make much more sense,'' he said, because the senator could bring home <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> for the Democrats. Even a partisan like <PERSON> Quackenbush </PERSON> conceded that in the South `` if you're from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, whether it's reality or perception, you're perceived as a liberal.'' But he contended that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> can win support in the South by emphasizing the idea that as a governor he has been `` a fiscal conservative.'' A big plus for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the South is the perception that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does not have the hold on voters that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had. `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s hold on Southern voters is not intense,'' said <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>. `` Nobody gets excited about <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>.
