<HEAD>Fiji's Marks First Anniversary Of Coup, Police Detain 18 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUVA, Fiji (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police on Saturday detained 18 people demonstrating against the government of <PERSON> Sitiveni </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION> marked the first anniversary of a military takeover that catapulted <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> to power. <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> celebrated his first year in power by attending an army parade where he exhorted soldiers to be considerate in preserving order this weekend. Troops remained on full alert as a precaution against possible violence, but no major trouble was reported. Police broke up a `` demonstration for democracy'' in downtown <LOCATION> Suva </LOCATION> while <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> attended the parade at the Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Barracks </PERSON> army headquarters. He told his troops to be mindful that some sections of the community had suffered as a result of the coup. The celebrations should not `` make things worse for people who might fear for their safety and their property,'' said <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON>, in an apparent reference to Indians, who outnumber ethnic Fijians in the 715,000 population. On May 14, 1987, <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON>, then a lieutenant colonel and third in the army's chain of command, led 10 masked soldiers into <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and arrested the elected Indian-majority coalition government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Timoci </PERSON> <PERSON> Bavadra </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> said he staged the coup to protect the interests of ethnic Fijians, who comprise 47 percent of the population. <PERSON> Bavadra </PERSON> had been in office only a month after defeating Prime Minister Ratu Sir <PERSON> Kamisese </PERSON> <PERSON> Mara </PERSON> in April elections. After the coup, an interim government was set up, but when it did n't please <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON>, he staged a second takeover on Sept. 25. Since then a nervous calm has settled over <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION>. The country's tourist-based economy is in shambles Gross domestic product is down 11 percent, sugar production _ the country's major cash crop _ is down 20.3 percent, tourism has plummeted 26.9 percent and the <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION> dollar has been devalued by 33 percent. At his home in <LOCATION> Viseisei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bavadra </PERSON> issued a statement vowing to continue to push for racial equality in <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION>, a group of 300 islands east of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. At the parade, <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> presented good conduct and meritorious service medals to six high-ranking army officers, several of whom were involved in the May 14, 1987 takeover. He told supporters that the recipients of the medals were `` shining examples'' to follow. Among the demonstrators were members of the <ORGANIZATION> Fiji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priest. The women, wearing black as a sign of mourning, carried placards denouncing the coup. Banners reading `` Only One Race _ The Human Race'' and `` Democracy Lives'' were torn down by police, who told the crowd to leave before it got out of control. When they refused to move, police herded some people into vans and took them away. Officials said the demonstrators were not charged and would be released later. Other demonstrators went to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andrew </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Presbysterian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION> where, watched from outside by police and soldiers, they held a religious service. On Saturday, the gates at the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> building remained locked. <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION> has had no Parliament since the coup and is now governed by an interim administration led by <PERSON> Mara </PERSON> while a new constitution is being written to guarantee power for ethnic Fijians. No other incidents were reported and the army was not much in evidence around the country except for guards at key points, such as power installations.
