<HEAD>Fire Chief Seeks Criminal Investigation of Security Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city's fire chief says he will seek a criminal investigation into an alleged delay by security guards in reporting a fire that ravaged the state's tallest skyscraper. Fire Chief <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> said Friday he intends to pursue legal action `` to the extent possible'' in the wake of the May 4 inferno that devastated four floors of the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> tower and left one man dead. Security personnel allegedly `` failed to notify the Fire Department of the fire in a timely manner, which is a violation of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Municipal Code,'' said Battalion Chief Dean <PERSON> Cathey </PERSON>. City officials said security guards reset fire alarms that went off on the 12th floor because they believed them to be false. They say guards delayed notifying authorities for seven minutes, allowing the blaze to spread through the 12th floor of the 62-floor office building. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Clauson </PERSON>, an official with <ORGANIZATION> Pedus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has disputed fire officials' version of events. <PERSON> Clauson </PERSON> said Pedus guards called the fire department about a minute after the alarms went off. Fire officials said that when fire alarms sounded a third time on the 12th floor, security officers sent a building engineer to the 12th floor to investigate. The worker, <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Handy </PERSON>, 24, died in the blaze. Manning spoke Friday during state senate hearings currently being conducted in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> on proposed fire-sprinkler legislation. A bill would require the installation of fire sprinklers in all high-rise buildings in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Clauson </PERSON> did not return telephone seeking comment about the investigation ordered by <PERSON> Manning </PERSON>.
