<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It was a week that should have come up all roses for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, with endorsements arriving from both the president and his only remaining Republican rival. But instead, thorns littered the way. In recent days, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his lieutenants have been forced to take the defensive on a host of issues, ranging from alleged drug trafficking by <LOCATION> Panamanian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to a lackluster endorsement from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Some of the troubles were minor irritants; others loomed as potential major problems as the vice president sought to translate his lock on the Republican presidential nomination into a fall general election strategy. Some of the recent problems besetting the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign: _ He unintentionally handed <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> a new issue with his characterization of the Democrat as `` the hustler from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'' in a speech to a GOP audience in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> seized upon the remark, saying it was offensive and showed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had `` started to panic.'' _ Despite enjoying a mathematical lock on the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination since the April 26 <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> primary, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won only 71 percent of the vote in last Tuesday's <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> primary Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., who had withdrawn from the race but whose name appeared on the ballot, captured 24 percent while <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> _ who endorsed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the following day to effectively end his own candidacy _ polled 5 percent _ Questions intensified about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s prior knowledge of alleged drug trafficking by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, fuel