Reagan </PERSON> was `` mortified'' to think that his words had been received as anything less than enthusiastic The campaign showed greater concern over the results of the <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> primary, which showed that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could not win solid GOP support in the state even while running virtually unopposed. Political analysts suggested the weak showing underscores a problem <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is likely to have in November throughout the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, where the farm economy, despite some recent signs of improvement, is still troubled. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s track record in the region has not been good. Although he later went on to win commanding victories in other states, he came in a disappointing third in the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> caucuses last February. He also lost to <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s primary, garnering only 19 percent to <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s 55 percent. And, in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did n't even bother to mount a major effort A straw poll there in February showed only 11 percent for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, compared to 43 percent for <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> and 28 percent for <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign strategists argued that the vice president's poor showings in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> reflect Kansan <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s popularity more than their candidate's vulnerability. `` <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> is still very popular -LRB- in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> -RRB-, and there was a very low turnout,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> deputy campaign manager <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>. `` And we'll take 71 percent of the vote any day of the week.'' Equally troubling to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s general-election prospects, according to analysts, was new survey evidence suggesting that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s popularity across party lines was unlikley to be transferred to his vice president. `` No president's popularity is,'' <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said. `` What's important is we're going to have the president as a great resource The president packs a lot of wallop out on the stump and everybody knows it.'' But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON>, a former consultant to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s presidential campaign, said `` there are problems for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that he's going to have to deal with'' and a lack of ready-made support among blue-collar Democrats is one of them. `` It's a problem he's going to to have to address through scheduling, speeches and through issues,'' <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> said. To date, said the consultant, `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has had a problem in articulating a message. He's been slow to do it. But people want a horse race and there are more Democrats than Republicans in the country. So it is nautral that the race is going to start out at least close, or maybe with -LRB- Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ahead.''
