<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon'sPulse     05-14 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon's Pulse,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Curtails Electromagnetic Pulse Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in a surprise move, has settled a lawsuit brought by two environmental groups by agreeing to sharply curtail research into a high-power electrical phenomenon known as electromagnetic pulse. The settlement, approved by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> late Friday, derails at least temporarily a program the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> had previously described as crucial to national security. Among other purposes, the research involved ways to `` harden'' crucial commnications and weapons guidance equipment against electrical surges triggered by nuclear explosions. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> must now determine whether its experiments, involving simulations powered by non-nuclear means, pose a danger to humans or wildlife. <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trends </ORGANIZATION>, one of the environmental groups which filed the lawsuit, hailed the agreement as `` the first court victory of this magnitude recognizing the threat posed by electronic or electrical pollution.'' `` We're extremely pleased,'' <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> added. `` This is the first recognition by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, and really the first on a national level at all, of a whole new environmental hazard facing all of us.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> declined to discuss the matter or its reasons for settling the case. The suit, filed in March 1987 by the Washington-based foundation and the <ORGANIZATION> Potomac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, `` sought essentially exactly what we got _ an end to high-power testing until an assessment is performed of the threat to the environment and human and animal health,'' <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> said. The settlement will shut down or sharply curtail the operations of a handful of <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> generators and, potentially, one <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> facility. Electromagnetic pulse, or <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION>, is a powerful wave, or surge, of electrical energy that is released by a nuclear explosion and which can travel long distances through the atmosphere or water. <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> became a matter of concern to the military in the early 1960s when the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> discovered a nuclear bomb detonated at high altitudes could generate a pulse so strong it could disable the electronic components used in computers, communications and guidance equipment. As a result of that discovery, military laboratories have studied the phenomenon for 25 years in the course of developing methods for enabling electronic weapons components to withstand <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION>. In recent years, <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> work also has been performed with an eye toward harnessing the energy pulses for offensive weapons, or `` zap guns.'' Under the terms of the settlement, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> must now shut down <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> generators located at <LOCATION> Woodbridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Redstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, and White Sands Missile Range, N.M. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> will be required to shut down its so-called Empress 1 generator at the <ORGANIZATION> Patuxent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, Md.; to refrain from starting construction of an Empress 2 system, and to significantly reduce the operating power of two other Patuxent generators. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, meantime, will be allowed to continue operating <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> simulators at <ORGANIZATION> Kirtland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, but only if it can provide documentation within 14 days demonstrating there is no discernible environmental risk from that operation. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, public affairs director for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weapons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Kirtland </LOCATION>, said `` We would be prepared'' to furnish the documentation. One of the five <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> simulators at <LOCATION> Kirtland </LOCATION> is one dubbed Trestle, a $ 58 million structure which enables scientists to imitate <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> effects upon aircraft electrical equipment. The other <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> facilities, which are located in closer proximity to populated areas, must remain shut down or operating only at low power levels until an environmental assessment of their operation is conducted, <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> said. The assessment probably will take five to six months, at which point all the generators may be returned to service but only at reduced power levels that ensure no electrical surge moves beyond the boundaries of the bases. The Pentagon must then satisfactorily complete a full-fledged environmental impact study _ a process that could take two years _ before the <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> generators can be used at their current power levels, <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> said. While the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> declined comment, <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> said he thought the government agreed to settle the case because the foundation's attorneys learned that two Army employees had warned the service against conducting <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> experiments at <LOCATION> Woodbridge </LOCATION> until an environmental assessment was completed When the foundation filed a motion to question the two workers, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers suddenly indicated a willingness to negotiate, <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> continued. `` They did n't want these guys to talk about the hazards,'' he said. `` We had them over a barrel.'' The foundation's lawsuit asserted that <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> experiments `` can affect human health directly, and through the disruption of electronic circuits in nuclear power plants, automobiles, computers, airplanes, phone lines and navigational systems, can cause potential catastrophies under many possible circumstances.''
</TEXT>
