<FIRST>r w AM-MaritimePaintings     05-14 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maritime Paintings,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Gallery Mounts Show of Works by Fitz Hugh Lane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The National Gallery of Art is mounting the first big show in 20 years of works by <PERSON> Fitz </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, known for his paintings of the first winner of the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s cup and of the first Cunard Line ship to cross the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. `` No other painter of the 19th century matched him in capturing the character of maritime <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, in portraying the reflective sheen of calm water or the agitated surface of windblown waves, the clarity of light-filled still air or the moist atmosphere of cloudy humid days,'' gallery director <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> says in a tribute appearing in the catalogue of the exhibit. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilmerding </PERSON>, the museum's deputy director and a specialist on <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, classes him just below the painter <PERSON> Winslow </PERSON> <PERSON> Homer </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> painted the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s cup race at least twice _ once in an unusual work that contains three views of the same yacht. That one is in the <LOCATION> Peabody </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. The other painting, lent to this show, shows the finale of the first race in 1851, with Britons waving their hats from a smaller boat while the Americans look the other way. A British side-wheeler packed with spectators is nearby. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> painted the Britannia, the first <ORGANIZATION> Cunard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> ship, entering <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> harbor in 1848, eight years after its first transatlantic voyage. Nearly all the 61 paintings in the show are of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> scenes. All are related to ships and the sea. There is a kind of glowing silence about them that critics say typifies the American movement now called `` luminism.'' <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> died in 1865, long before the term was invented. The exhibit opens Sunday in the gallery's West Building and will be there until Sept. 5. It then will move to the <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> from Oct. 5 to Dec. 31. The exhibit has been financed by a grant from the <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
