<HEAD>Reagan Poised to Veto Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Saturday that while workers should get as much warning as possible before they're fired or laid off, he can not sign a trade bill requiring such notification because it `` threatens to destroy jobs.'' `` It is unfortunate, but I have no choice but to send this back to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said of the 1,000-page trade measure. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the veto would occur in the coming week. In his weekly radio address, delivered from Camp David, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> zeroed in on the battle over the plant-closing section of the bill, which is expected to become a campaign issue in the fall elections. While the administration supports much of the bill, it faults the requirement that companies notify workers at least 60 days in advance of layoffs or a plant shutdown. The issue should be decided between labor and management, not government, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> argued. `` Let me state very clearly, I believe businesses should give workers and communities just as much warning as they can when it looks as though layoffs or plant closings are going to become unavoidable,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` It's the humane thing to do.'' `` But when big government gets in the middle of something like this, dictating all its rules and regulations, the humane way has a way of becoming inhumane,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. The president contended that the requirement would force struggling businesses to shut down at crucial times, and that management needs the flexibility of using temporary layoffs to get a business back on its feet. It would also keep companies from adding workers if it would subject them to the bill's requirements, the president said. Although there are exceptions in the bill for companies that find themselves in serious financial trouble, but <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> derided them as `` too vague and unclear to be workable.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> argued that `` one independent study'' showed that if the plant-closing provision had been in effect from 1982 to 1986, `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> would have almost half a million fewer jobs.'' He did not cite the source of the study. In the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the nation needs the bill to combat the worst trade deficit in history _ $ 171 billion. `` It weakens our country, depresses wages, reduces our standard of living,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> argued. He took issue with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s threat to veto the bill over the plant closing provision. `` This bill simply ... asks the nation's biggest employers to give American workers at least 60 days' notice before they close another plant. That's not too much to ask. Not sufficient cause, Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, to abandon the work of three years and scrap this vitally needed legislation,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker contended that `` 86 percent of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people support this plant closing provision.'' `` Top management knows in advance when its service is no longer required and builds golden parachutes worth millions of dollars for its comfort. Ca n't we give the workers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at least 60 days to get their lives in order, to get new training, to cushion the blow?'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked. Democrats sent the bill to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last week with a parade of razzle-dazzle events and photo sessions, and have threatened to hit Republicans in the fall with the issue if <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoes the measure. The bill would overhaul the system for imposing import curbs to retaliate against international trade violations and aid American industries threatened by increased foreign competition. While it cleared the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by a 312-107 margin _ more than the two-thirds needed to override a presidential veto _ it was approved in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by 63-36, three votes shy of the margin sufficient to override.
</TEXT>
