<FIRST>r w AM-Democrats-Text     05-14 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Text,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s weekly radio address. It was delivered Saturday by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. Good afternoon. This is <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. Let's talk a little bit together about the most important thing to come out of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this year. The new trade bill we sent to the president this week can be a big victory for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. It can help us get back on track to being No. 1 in the world. Last year, our country suffered the worst trade deficit in our history _ $ 171 billion. We paid that much more for foreign goods than we sold in American-made products. And that can be devastating. It weakens our country, depresses wages, reduces our standard of living. In all, the trade deficit cost the average American family about $ 3,000 last year. Because of this, we're no longer No. 1 in per capita gross national product. Last year we fell to No. 3. Because of these trade deficits, our country, which was the No. 1 creditor nation in the world just five years ago, is the world's largest debtor nation today And foreign ownership of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> banks, American farms and real estate, and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s marketable securities increases by about 25 percent each year. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can do better than that. We must do better than that. The new trade bill will put us on an upward path. Its contents are summed up in three important words _ rules, tools and schools. New rules to make a level playing field, to give <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> products a chance on foreign markets. We ask other countries to treat our goods just as we treat their goods on our markets _ no better, no worse. New tools to strengthen our industrial base, to modernize our plants, to improve our American productivity. Better schools to prepare <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children for increasing world competition and to hone and sharpen the skills of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s work force <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> needs this bill. And so we plead with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>: Please sign the trade bill. Give <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> a chance to excel on world markets again. Let `` Made in the <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>'' become a badge of quality and value throughout the world. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has threatened to veto this bill simply because it asks the nation's biggest employers to give American workers at least 60 days' notice before they close another plant. That's not too much to ask. Not sufficient cause, Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, to abandon the work of three years and scrap this vitally needed legislation. Eighty-six percent of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people support this plant closing provision, this notification to workers. They say it's only fair. Top management knows in advance when its service is no longer required and builds golden parachutes worth millions of dollars for its comfort. Ca n't we give the workers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at least 60 days to get their lives in order, to get new training, to cushion the blow? In the name of the 2 million American workers who lost their jobs last year because of plant shutdowns and layoffs _ many of those plants going overseas, two-thirds of them given no notice at all _ Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, we ask you to sign this bill and let it become law. In the name of <PERSON> Patsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and 117 employees who lost their jobs in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> -RRB- with only one day notice, please sign the trade bill. In the name of <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Schrenko </PERSON> and 160 iron workers at a plant in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> -RRB- which closed with only 15 minutes' notice, please sign this bill, Mr. President. In the name of <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON> and 397 workers who lost their jobs at a plant in <LOCATION> Eau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, please sign the bill. In the name of these and others in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s work force, good Americans who want to help us revive this country, we call on you, Mr. <PERSON> President </PERSON>, to consider the equities and let this vital American initiative begin.
