<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-communist insurgents Saturday offered limited amnesty to Afghan government soldiers as Soviet troops prepared for the start of their withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gulbadin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, chairman of the seven-party Afghan guerrilla alliance, said Afghan security forces who voluntarily surrender within four weeks after Soviet troops have left their districts would not be tried for war crimes. `` Once captured ... they will face Islamic courts,'' <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said at a news conference at the alliance's <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION> headquarters. He did not say what punishments they would face if convicted. The insurgents have vowed to continue and intensify their fight until the last of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the Marxist government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> falls. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said the rebels had postponed a swap of one Soviet prisoner for 25 captured guerrillas. He said his group will keep Soviet prisoners until it establishes an Islamic government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He did not divulge how many Soviet or Afghan army troops were being held. The leader of the extremist <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-E-Islami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said his party will hold onto Soviet prisoners and try to exchange them for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and other high-ranking members of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION>. He said the guerrillas want to put <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and his associates on trial for war crimes. Western observers disagree on how long <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> can stay in power once his 100,000-strong security force is left to face the guerrillas alone. The rebels claim to have overrun 50 posts and garrisons, mostly in eastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, in the last month as <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops have headed toward <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in preparation for their withdrawal, which begins Sunday. `` May 15 means the defeat of Soviet forces militarily in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the start of the puppet regime's collapse,'' said <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>. `` The <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> withdrawal is the first phase of our victory.'' `` May 15 also proves that in wars, modern weapons and number of troops do not matter,'' he said, adding, `` no power, however arrogant, is able to crush a nation committed to its faith.'' <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said the guerrillas would be willing to talk to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> advisers, who will oversee the nine-month Soviet troop withdrawal. The 50-man force, headed by Gen. <PERSON> Rauli </PERSON> <PERSON> Helminen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, is composed of military personnel mainly from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Good Offices Mission for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> said that starting Sunday the group will inspect Soviet, <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> and guerrilla military bases in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and refugee camps in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The guerrilla alliance, composed of four Moslem extremist groups and three moderate traditionalist parties, has begun forming its own alternative government. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said the new Islamic-style government will establish itself inside <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in the near future. He has given no date. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s party seized power in a bloody 1978 coup. Soviet troops intervened in December 1979, replacing one pro-Moscow government with another.
