<HEAD>Elderly Man Charged In Nursing Home Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An elderly man has been charged with killing a fellow nursing home resident by striking him with a cane during an argument over an ashtray, police said. <PERSON> Adolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Rentell </PERSON>, 86, was arrested and charged with criminal homicide Friday at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where he has been a patient for a week. He was arraigned in the hospital but will remain hospitalized indefinitely for psychiatric evaluation, according to city homicide detectives. Rentell is charged in the death of <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassanelli </PERSON>, 87. <PERSON> Vassanelli </PERSON> died last Sunday, two days after he was attacked in a hallway of <ORGANIZATION> Negley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a nursing home. An autopsy showed <PERSON> Vassanelli </PERSON> died of meningitis, a complication from infection and broken facial bones caused by blows to his face. The attack came after <PERSON> Vassanelli </PERSON>, who was in a wheelchair, asked <PERSON> Rentell </PERSON> to stop spitting into an ashtray <PERSON> Vassanelli </PERSON> was using, police said. Despite <PERSON> Rentell </PERSON>'s age and questions about his mental state, police say he was charged because they believe he was aware of his actions at the time of the attack.
