<HEAD>Afghan Pullout: The Beginning of the End of Soviet Military Role</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `On Saturday...' to ADD rocket blast; SUBS
14th graf, ``We consider ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
guerrillas offering limited amnesty to Afghan troops. PICKS up 15th
graf, `Gromov, who ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos KAB3, KAB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bloodied but unbroken, the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> begins pulling out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Sunday amid threats of guerrilla harassment and grave doubts about the future of the Marxist government it leaves behind. On the eve of the withdrawal, the Soviet commander in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> denied his men had been defeated in the brutal war that has claimed an estimated 10,000 Soviet lives. But politically, the fruits of the 8 -LCB- - year Soviet armed intervention seem meager Militarily, the Soviet presence has proved far from decisive. On Saturday, in the Afghan capital of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, a bomb exploded inside a truck near reviewing stands built for a ceremony honoring the departing Soviet troops. Eleven Afghan civilians were reported killed. Later, three rockets hit a village outside <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, killing four people. Since Dec. 27, 1979, when the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> sent tanks and troops into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, Soviet soldiers have been fighting to prop up the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION>, but they have failed to break the back of a nationwide anti-Marxist insurgency. Acknowledging the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s unwillingness to keep bearing the military and diplomatic costs of the intervention, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> signed U.N.-brokered accords in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on April 14 that commit the Soviets to a nine-month pullout, beginning Sunday. As the first of an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops prepare to come home, one major question is how _ or if _ the Moscow-aligned regime of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, which claims just 40,000 regular soldiers of its own, can survive. The first Soviets to leave will be from a motor-rifle division garrisoned at <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, a dusty provincial town 30 miles from the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> border, military officials and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> media have said. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, Soviet commander in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, said Saturday more than 1,000 soldiers would leave <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> on Sunday and that a quarter of the entire Soviet contingent would be home by the time President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> visits <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on May 29-June 2. In recent days, Soviet media have issued alarming reports about increasing guerrilla activity, perhaps to ready public opinion for losses during the withdrawal, or to stress that the pullout will heighten the likelihood of bloodshed among the Afghan factions locked in a 10-year-old civil war. Soviet television took its viewers Thursday to the <LOCATION> Kabul-Kandahar-Herat </LOCATION> road, a 650-mile crescent-shaped track that links three of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s major cities, for a taped interview with a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officer assigned to screen the pullout. `` The activity of armed opposition bands has been sharply increasing,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> N.V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON>, who spoke as a truck convoy crawled along the hilly road in back of him. `` The road will apparently become an objective for which they will fight till the bitter end.'' Guerrilla commanders, who refused to be party to the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreements, have vowed to give the Soviets no respite during the pullout. <PERSON> Gulbaddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, head of the seven-party rebel alliance, offered a limited amnesty to Afghan forces who surrender within four weeks after Soviet troops leave their districts. He said Saturday in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> that those who surrendered in time would not be tried for war crimes. But he said those who do n't surrender and are captured will face Islamic courts <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>, who spoke at a news conference in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, said the rebels had recently received antitank weapons, but warned: `` If any group tries to use any weapons, retribution will be quick and severe.'' Asked if the pullout was a defeat, the 44-year-old commander said: `` The Soviet Army will return home after fulfilling its internationalist duty ... During the war, not a single unit retreated in the face of the enemy, so we can not speak of a military defeat.'' <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON>'s remarks were made available to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a pool report from the British news agency <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> was excluded from the pool because of questions it asked <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> in the Afghan capital last month. Most of the Soviets will be traveling by land, rather than by airlift. For some convoys, the trek to Soviet border cities like <LOCATION> Termez </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kushka </LOCATION> is expected to take three days or more, often through rugged, mountainous terrain where the rebels have been active in the past. Air cover for the retreating columns may be a crucial problem, as the insurgents have U.S.-made Stinger missiles, deadly against low-flying helicopters and planes. Fearing the heat-seating Stinger, the Soviets and Afghans in 1986 virtually ceased using their aircraft for ground support missions. As they withdraw, the Soviets will hand over more than 170 military bases with equipment worth $ 1 billion to their <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> allies, <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, 41, a burly, mustachioed Marxist who is a former head of the <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> secret police, has scoffed when asked whether the departure of his Soviet allies will bring about the downfall of his government. However, many of the dozens of posts handed over to his army in recent weeks reportedly have been overrun by well-armed guerrillas. Soviet media reports have said Soviet soldiers believe they have honorably performed their duty in coming to the support of a beleagured government, but the media have made no secret of the men's desire to return home. In the television interview, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON>, whose detachment will protect other units as they withdraw, pointed to his men and said: `` They say we will certainly envy the first columns that go home.''
