<HEAD>GOP Senate Leaders See Good Chance for Shrinking Budget Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican leaders in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> reassured the nation's top business executives Saturday that the outlook is good for shrinking the federal budget deficit. The Business Council, composed of 61 chief executives of the nation's largest corporations, heard from Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, and Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>., as the group wrapped up a two-day conference The sessions of the elite council are private, but <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> told reporters before speaking to the executives, `` I'm not one of those who is going to go before this business group and predict gloom and fear.'' <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> is ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and a member of a national bipartisan commission that began meeting last week to devise ways to lower the deficit. The business executives, as they opened their twice-a-year conference at The Homestead, a plush resort in the mountains of southwestern <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, issued a generally upbeat assessment of the nation's economic prospects this year, but warned that the budget deficit remains `` disturbingly high'' during such a period of good times. <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pratt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Pfizer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a health care corporation, said many business leaders enjoying the moderate economic growth have a sense of `` living on borrowed time'' because of government red ink. `` I think most of us still regard the budget deficit as the No. 1 problem facing us,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilpatrick </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> CIGNA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, an insurance company. The executives, in a forecast representing a consensus of member corporation's chief economists, said that the budget deficit would rise from $ 150.2 billion last year to $ 154 billion both this year and in 1989. The <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates the deficit will be $ 157 billion in 1988. But <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> said `` we've made significant strides'' and predicted the government would `` very easily'' meet the $ 136 billion, 1989 target of the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law. He said he did not want to prematurely divulge the positions he will be taking in the deliberations of the national commission. But, he said, `` I do n't think it's as simple, as some are saying, that we ought to just look out there for some big tax, just so it's not income or corporate income tax.'' `` We better be guarded about taxes with the American economy doing as well as it is,'' he said. <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, who is deputy Republican leader in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, spoke to the executives Friday night. He told reporters Saturday that the government must limit the growth of federal entitlement programs to achieve any meaningful reduction in the deficit. `` When we deal honestly with <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, Social Security, veteran's benefits, then we'll get something done. All else is dancing in the night,' he said. He said he believed the national commission would propose a sensible package because the co-chairmen, former <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, `` are pretty gutsy guys.'' On another matter, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said he was optimistic that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, despite a tight schedule, will pass a second and better trade bill after President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoes the bill sent to him last week. <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said two key Democratic leaders, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, were unlikely to let the legislation die because of strong support in their home state for repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil, which is included in the massive trade bill. The president is expected to reject the legislation because of a provision that would require companies to give 60 days notice of plant closings and major layoffs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, who went before the business group on Friday, said the plant closing provision was `` onerous'' because it would provide a legal basis for challenging virtually every closing or layoff.
