<HEAD>Death Stalks India-Pakistan Frontier In Punjab</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL3</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> BURJ </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> India-Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ As night falls on the rugged frontier, the rattle of guns of Indian border guards serves as a warning to potential Sikh infiltrators and arms merchants who try to cross into <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The guards take target practice 500 yards from the frontier to warm up for the nightlong vigil. In the past eight weeks, at least 56 people have died in 47 encounters between Indian <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and would-be infiltrators or arms smugglers. `` The days of the war game are over. We are faced with a situation where we must stop infiltration from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> by any means,'' border force Inspector General <PERSON> Parkash </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said at the <LOCATION> Burj </LOCATION> border post in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> wants to close the border with fences, men and strict vigilance. The urgency to seal the 348-mile section of border in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> stems from escalating violence in the state, where hundreds of people have died in <LOCATION> Sikh </LOCATION> separatist violence this year. Sikh militants have been fighting since 1982 for an independent Sikh homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s border with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> stretches 1,836 miles, running through the Indian states of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rajasthan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>. It is a nervous border. Both nations station military forces in nearby garrisons in memory of the three wars they have fought in the last 41 years. `` It is like firecrackers strewn all over the place. What is needed is just a matchstick to start full-scale confrontation,'' a border official told journalists who were taken to the border on a government tour for foreign news organizations. He spoke on condition of anonymity. The Sikh terrorist campaign has prompted the Indian government to take drastic steps. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of sheltering and arming the Sikhs, charges repeatedly denied by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. An estimated 15,000 Indian border guards are deployed along the <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> sector of the frontier. In addition, 40,000 Indian army men are garrisoned in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, subject to call-up on two hours' notice. Reporters saw Indian foot patrols in full combat readiness at <LOCATION> Burj </LOCATION>, 26 miles west of the <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> holy city of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. At a nearby 100-foot high observation tower, two guards were looking through binoculars and keeping their foot patrols informed about movement on the Pakistani side. After sundown, the tower guards use night-vision devises. Whenever a potential infiltrator is spotted, the patrols are alerted. They first ask the would-be infiltrators to stop and identify themselves. `` We give them a one-minute response time. If they try to run or fail to respond, we fire,'' said <PERSON> Vijendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Sirohi </PERSON>, the border force's deputy inspector general for the <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> sector. In an effort to stop infiltration, the Indian government has started fencing vulnerable sections with barbed wire. Senior officers in charge of border operations and intelligence say Sikh violence can only be contained if infiltration from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is checked. `` The oxygen for the Sikh terrorists is coming from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. If we can stop the oxygen supply, terrorism will die,'' said <PERSON> Saran </PERSON> <PERSON> Prasad </PERSON>, chief of operations at the border force's headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. `` Before we would have hesitated to name <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, but now it is as clear as daylight _ I mean their help to terrorists,'' <PERSON> Prasad </PERSON> said. Reporters were shown arms and ammunition the officers said were captured from infiltrators. The weapons included rocket-propelled grenade launchers, Soviet-designed AK-47 rifles and pistols. `` It is the AK-47 that worries us the most,'' <PERSON> Prasad </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has nothing to match the AK-47, whose firepower and light weight make it an ideal weapon for untrained gunmen. Border troops are equipped with single-shot rifles, in addition to light machine guns that must be mounted before firing.
