<HEAD>Morals Offenders To Be Whipped In Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday approved a law under which people who offend `` public morals'' will receive 74 lashes. State-run Iranian television, monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said the law would apply to those who take any action `` or pretend to take any action'' that hurts public morals. It did not spell out the offenses. Under <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s Islamic government, husbands and wives are forbidden from kissing or showing physical affection in public. Such actions are often referred to as offending morality. After approval by the council, the law took effect immediately. The beatings are administered with a metal-cored flexible whip with an outer covering. Men are sometimes beaten in public, women always in private. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s revolutionary legal code has an elaborate list of punishments, with precise numbers of lashes given for each category of offense.
