^By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the hours after his car plunged off the bridge at <LOCATION> Chappaquiddick </LOCATION>, Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> wanted to tell police that <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopechne </PERSON> was alone in the car, according to a new book about the accident. In an account attributed to <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> cousin <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> told <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> and a friend, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Markham </PERSON>, the morning after the accident that `` I'm going to say that <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> was driving.'' <PERSON> Kopechne </PERSON> drowned in the accident, which has shadowed <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s political career for 19 years The book, by <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Damore </PERSON>, is `` Senatorial Privilege: The Chappaquiddick Coverup,'' and is purportedly based, in part, on the first extensive interviews <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> has ever given for publication. <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Markham </PERSON> went with <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> to the bridge shortly after the accident to try to rescue <PERSON> Kopechne </PERSON> from the submerged car. A statement issued by <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said: `` As the record shows, no reputable publisher would touch this book. The charges about senator <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> are false. The book is an irresponsible rehash of all the old rumor and innuendo, and we have no intention of making any further comment.'' <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON>, a lawyer who is now a member of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, did not return repeated telephone calls over the past week. Contacted recently by the <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, he said: `` My God, that was 19 years ago. It's just not worthy of discussing anymore.'' The book is being published by <ORGANIZATION> Regnery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gateway </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative publishing house based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, after being rejected by a number of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> publishers. <PERSON> Damore </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Saybrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, is a former <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION> resident who has written several books, including a flattering account of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s years on the cape. <ORGANIZATION> Random </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had given <PERSON> Damore </PERSON> a $ 250,000 contract, but canceled it, saying an early version of the book was too unwieldy and that the author failed to provide tape recordings to authenticate the <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> interviews. Penthouse magazine canceled an excerpt plan on ground that <PERSON> Damore </PERSON> could n't verify key parts of the <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> interviews. But <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> campaign aide and now a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> magistrate on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview that he was present for nearly all of the <LOCATION> Damore-Gargan </LOCATION> sessions, in 1983. He declined to go over specifics, but vouched for the book's accuracy. <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> also read the book and made corrections prior to publication, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. According to <PERSON> Damore </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> told him <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> concocted the proposal that authorities be told <PERSON> Kopechne </PERSON> was alone in the senator's Oldsmobile when it plunged off tiny Dike Bridge over an inlet on the east side of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> island. The accident occurred the weekend of July 18-19, 1969. <PERSON> Kopechne </PERSON> was one of six women known as the `` boiler room girls'' who had worked on <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s 1968 presidential campaigns and who attended a party <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> had organized. `` <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was having alternative ideas about the situation,'' wrote author <PERSON> Damore </PERSON>. `` Why could n't <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> have been driving the car? Why could n't she have let him off and driven to the ferry herself and made a wrong turn?'' `` <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> asked to be brought back to the cottage to establish the story. After a while he could leave. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> suggested that when he was back -LRB- in <LOCATION> Edgartown </LOCATION> -RRB-, <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> could ` discover' the accident and report to police that <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> had been alone in the car.'' But <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> purportedly rejected the idea, noting that the trio did not even know if Miss <PERSON> Kopechne </PERSON> could drive or had a license. The senator testified at an official inquest that he `` had full intention of reporting'' the accident when the trio returned to the <LOCATION> Chappaquiddick </LOCATION> ferry landing and the senator swam back to <LOCATION> Edgartown </LOCATION> alone. But he said the tide was pulling him out and `` for the second time that evening I knew I was going to drown.'' The next morning <PERSON> Markham </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> arrived at the <LOCATION> Edgartown </LOCATION> hotel to find a freshly shaven and neatly dressed <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> chatting with several acquaintances about sailing on the hotel balcony. He had not reported the accident. `` I told them about my own thoughts and feelings as I swam across that channel ... that somehow when they arrived in the morning that they were going to say that <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> was still alive,'' the senator has said. The book said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not decide to tell police that he was driving until speaking by telephone with aide <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>. It took about 10 hours for <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> to report the accident, an action that he later called `` irrational and indefensible and inexcusable and inexplicable.'' The senator pleaded guilty to a charge of leaving the scene of an accident. He received a two-month suspended sentence and had his license revoked for a year. A manuscript of the book, which is scheduled to be published June 23, was made available to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Washingtonian magazine said it plans to run excerpts in its June issue. The book quotes <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> as saying to <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, in 1982, `` I've given you 30 years of my life and what do I have to show for it I'm a fool in the eyes of my own children because of <LOCATION> Chappaquiddick </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Markham </PERSON>, who did not talk to the author, declined comment. The book, reporting the scene on the night of the accident, said <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> watched <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Markham </PERSON>'s rescue operation and called out: `` Can you see her? Is she in there'?'' The account continued: `` <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> saw the senator stretched out on the bridge on his back. Hands clapsed behind his head, knees drawn up, the senator was looking into the sky, rocking back and forth, repeating, ` Oh my God. What am I going to do'?''
