<HEAD>Report: U.S. Focus on Drugs, Nicaragua Misses Latin Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cocaine and communism have dominated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> this decade, while the region's festering economic and political problems are being neglected, experts warn in an 84-page report issued here. `` Miami Report II'' was prepared by bankers, oil executives, clergymen and academics led by <PERSON> Ambler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moss </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. It follows up on the group's first report in 1984, which accurately forecast a gradually worsening economic crisis in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` Without a solution, there will be severe erosion of fragile democracies in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Moss </PERSON> said in an interview Friday. He is now dean of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>. `` You ca n't run a democracy when the economy is going to hell,'' he said. Since the early 1980s, money has steadily flowed out of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, depriving the underdeveloped nations of desperately needed capital, says the study, which was released Friday. By the end of 1987, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was staggering under a debt burden of $ 460 billion. The authors say the region is mired in its worst depression since the 1930s. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s elected President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>, who has had to put down attempted military coups, frequently warns the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that his region's economic troubles threaten its political stability. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy has ignored the deeper problems, concentrating instead on battling communism in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Moss </PERSON> said. `` There has been almost an obssession with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to the exclusion of everything else,'' <PERSON> Moss </PERSON> said. `` In the absolute worst case, we could send troops into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> _ but we ca n't send them into every country in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The other dominant theme in U.S.-Latin relations has been narcotics trafficking, says <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> professor <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagley </PERSON>, who specializes in international relations and prepared the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Report II section on drug trafficking. He pointed to the inability of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to either unseat or prosecute <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on drug charges. `` Our argument is that there are many other problems equally fundamental,'' <PERSON> Bagley </PERSON> said in a separate interview Friday. `` By failing to deal with these problems, the Noriegas of the world can flourish.'' Even in fighting the traffickers, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has failed to come up with concrete anti-drug aid to financially strapped countries, or with programs to cut <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand, <PERSON> Bagley </PERSON> said. But cocaine rhetoric and get-tough policies _ instead of deeper economic issues _ dominate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, he said. `` This is a lost decade for democracy and development in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bagley </PERSON> said. The report acknowledges it is timed for the 1988 presidential elections, and calls on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> voters to demand more substance in the candidates' <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> policy. A section of the report by Msgr. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> archdiocese also calls for a more realistic immigration policy, criticizing the government for narrowing its definition of political asylum to thwart Latin and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> immigrants. Miami Report II's main focus is economic, however, and the authors offer what they say are moderate policies to curb the departure of capital from the region. They call for Latin American nations themselves to adopt internal policies that reassure investors. <PERSON> Moss </PERSON> noted that <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, with a foreign debt of $ 53 billion, has `` flight capital'' of $ 39 billion deposited outside the country by Argentines worried about the nation's political and economic health. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy _ or lack of it _ takes a large share of the blame, the report says, and must be changed. One suggestion is for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> to lower interest rates on loans made directly to smaller countries. Another is for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to increase funding available for <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> through the <ORGANIZATION> Inter-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>.
