<SECOND>AM-Buddhist-Tourism,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>UI Team Helping India Develop Buddhist Sites For Tourism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 University of Illinois landscape architects are working on designs to help the government of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> attract more tourists to key Buddhist religious sites. University officials will go to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> this summer to present plans for redeveloping <PERSON> Sarnath </PERSON>, where <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON> delivered his first sermon more than 2,500 years ago. `` It gives our students hands-on experience, and it is an exciting challenge to develop tourism there,'' said <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellafiore </PERSON>, head of the university's Department of Landscape Architecture. `` People can see a totally different religion and culture.'' <PERSON> Sarnath </PERSON>, in the northern part of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, contains landmark structures such as a temple, a museum and architectural ruins. But, there also are mud houses, cycle rickshaws, and streets lined with vendors selling everything from silk to peanuts. One goal for the university team was to create designs that suit both religious and recreational activities at <LOCATION> Sarnath </LOCATION> and would cut down conflicts between the two. `` Some people come for religious devotion,'' said <PERSON> Bellafiore </PERSON>. `` Others picnic on the grass next to the temple with a ghetto-blaster and barbecue meat, and that is very offensive.'' So, the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> students and faculty visited <PERSON> Sarnath </PERSON> and returned with pictures and ideas, then spent months on campus early this year developing plans for improving the site. Graduate student <PERSON> Miki </PERSON> <PERSON> Stuebe </PERSON> concentrated on the zoo, creating more natural settings for animals in place of the small cages now used. For example, one of her drawings depicts an island for the zoo's monkeys. `` We want to tie into <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> concepts like compassion for all living things,'' she said. One alternative in the plan calls for moving the zoo away from the key religious area. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Blume-Weaver </PERSON>, another graduate student, rolled out a drawing of proposed new footpaths intended to keep people from walking on the architectural ruins. Around some <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> structures, the plans show two paths _ one for religious pilgrims who spend much more time there, and another for tourists who want to walk past more quickly. In other areas of <LOCATION> Sarnath </LOCATION>, the plans along a main road include trees more typical of those found during <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON>'s time, concepts for tourist-related market spaces and hedges to restrict the movement of farm animals into the site. For overnight tourists, there are concepts for new housing designed to blend in with the architecture of the current village. `` We do n't want a chichi resort in the midst of abject poverty,'' said <PERSON> Bellafiore </PERSON>, who hopes the housing will be decorated with pottery and weavings by village craftsmen to help the local economy. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourism </ORGANIZATION> agreed on this project. The only cost was transportation and food and lodging in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> for the university team, said <PERSON> Bellafiore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bellafiore </PERSON> said he will return to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> with other university officials to deliver the designs that will provide the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> government with alternatives that are `` not enormously expensive.'' `` I think our plans will satisfy <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s goal to increase tourism,'' said <PERSON> Blume-Weaver </PERSON>. `` I'd also like to see the ruins better preserved, and I'd like to see the place respected more as a religious site.'' Similar designs may be developed by the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> team for other <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> sites in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>.
