<HEAD>Mitterrand Dissolves Assembly and Calls Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 9 grafs with Giscard d'Estaing opposing dissolution.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> dissolved the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday and announced that parliamentary elections will be held June 5 and June 12. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> made the announcement in a nationwide television address. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said he made the decision after his new premier, <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>, informed him `` that despite his efforts, he did not believe he could bring together a solid and stable majority that all governments need to carry out their programs well.'' <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> said Friday he had sought support from centrists in the 577-seat Assembly for his government and received a negative response. In his three-minute address, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> deplored the fact that `` the opening -LRB- to the center -RRB- that I sought could not be brought about to the extent that I wished. Therefore, it was my duty to draw the appropriate conclusions. A few seconds ago I signed a decree dissolving the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>.'' He said the two-round election would be held on the first and second Sundays of June. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> was re-elected to a second term May 8 and appointed <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON> his premier after conservative Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who had run against <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> for president, resigned. According to an opinion poll to be published Sunday in the Journal du Dimanche, 47 percent of the French favored dissolution of the Assembly, while 28 percent opposed dissolution. The poll indicated that the Socialists, the largest party in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, would get 41 percent of the vote, 24 percent would go to the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic, and 15 percent would go to the center-right Union for French Democracy. The rest of the vote would go to minor parties on the left and the right, the poll indicated. Nearly 20 percent of those polled said they would not vote. Former President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing, a prominent center-right leader, told <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> earlier he should convene the Assembly before deciding on dissolution. <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> said in a letter to <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> the action should come `` after a serious discussion on what is possible and what is not.'' He said he opposed dissolution for two reasons. `` The French now will have to vote five times in 15 months'' in various elections, which <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> described as `` great waste of time and energy.'' He also said that the central problem facing the country was how to get the left and the right to work together. `` How can we achieve this if the first decision, before any attempt to work together, is to send the two camps face to face against each other in every electoral district in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> acted six days after winning a second-seven year term with 54 percent of the vote. He also dissolved the Assembly after winning his first term in 1981 and was rewarded with a victory by the Socialists in the legislative elections that followed. The last dissolution before that was pronounced by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON> on May 30, 1968 after the student uprising in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>.
