new union unclear, adds quotes and details. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists, educators and other intellectuals Saturday formed communist <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s first new trade union in 40 years. It was not known whether the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> would be independent of the government-approved union structure, said a participant who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` You certainly can not compare the -LRB- union -RRB- with the Polish trade union Solidarity, because it is a non-political organization,'' he said. Solidarity, the Soviet bloc's first independent union federation, was banned in 1981. The participant said about 400 people attended the founding session and elected a 59-member steering committee. The meeting was to take place at the <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Faculty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budapest </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eoetvoes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lorand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, but it had to be shifted to the <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, a cultural club, because the university rector withdrew an earlier permit granted by the dean. The new union includes representatives of natural, social and technical sciences, higher education and research institutes. Other members include laboratory assistants and unemployed researchers. interests were ignored by the official public employees' union. Spokesmen said it would fight to improve members' working conditions, increase funds for research and reduce layoffs. `` They intend to campaign for a science policy that consistently upholds their common interests and for eliminating restrictions hindering science and education,'' government radio said. Participants at the meeting voted to maintain contact with the official <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION>. Steering committee member <PERSON> Csaba </PERSON> <PERSON> Oeri </PERSON> said the union `` is part of the existing Hungarian trade union movement.'' But he did not say whether the new union would join the council. Two council members attended the session but did not address it. <PERSON> Gyoergy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerekes </PERSON>, another steering committee member, said council president <PERSON> Sandor </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaspar </PERSON> told him it was not hostile to such initiatives but did not want the meeting to take place. Other prominent steering committee members include sociologist <PERSON> Elemer </PERSON> <PERSON> Hankiss </PERSON>, <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Szalai </PERSON>, a sociologist and mathematician, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanak </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s best known historians and <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Ancsel </PERSON>, a philosopher and member of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>.
