l Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and its South African allies. Most of the fighting is in southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The South African Press Association quoted South African officials as saying the South African delegates `` feared a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> ploy to have a last hard strike in order to make their subsequent withdrawal diplomatically more palatable.'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roelof </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Pik </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, who led the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> delegation, `` apparently stressed that if this was the intention ... <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> would pay a heavy price and the Cubans would be severely punished,'' the press association reported. In <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, the independent weekly Expresso Saturday quoted unidentified sources as saying 8,600 Cuban soldiers landed in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> by plane and ship in a two-week period at the end of April and the beginning of May. The report said the reinforcements included 2,000 elite Cuban soldiers known as rangers, a force that previously has not sent troops to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, and 200 helicopter pilots. Expresso said the Cubans landed in the Angolan capital, <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>, and five other towns without the knowledge or approval of Angolan authorities, including President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>.
