<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb Saturday ripped through a truck parked near reviewing stands to be used for ceremonies marking the withdrawal of Soviet troops. Eleven Afghans, including a baby, were killed. Residents said three rockets later hit a village on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, killing four people and wounding four others. The official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> put the death toll at three. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, blamed both attacks on Afghan guerrillas and said one of those responsible for the 5:45 a.m. truck attack was arrested. <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevruk </PERSON> reported that 11 people were killed and 12 injured in the explosion. The blast killed a baby and an 11-year-old girl, and all the casualties were Afghan civilians, according to a Western photographer on the scene. Most appeared to have been occupants of nearby homes destroyed by the impact of the explosion, he said. `` When the bomb exploded some of the houses nearby just collapsed,'' said the photographer. The blast was so great that it shattered the windows of a bus depot across the river, 300 yards away and left a crater 20 feet wide and 10 feet deep. Soviet troops arrived afterward, the photographer said by telephone. The blast demolished embankment walls on both sides of the river that threads through this ancient capital. Blood was visible on the gates of a nearby factory and personal belongings, including carpet slippers, were scattered in the street. The bomb had been planted in a large truck that lay badly mangled at the scene. Last month, six people were killed and 49 wounded in another bomb blast along the river on the 10th anniversary of the April 1978 revolution that brought a Marxist government to power in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and triggered widespread insurrection. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the rockets Saturday hit the village of <LOCATION> Chamane </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Baraqi </LOCATION>, killing an old man and two children. Residents said one rocket hit a hut, killing two children inside and that an elderly man and another child were killed by debris. The village is located about a half-mile from the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. At a news conference for foreign journalists who gathered for the beginning of the Soviet withdrawal, <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said his government will survive because it offers peace. He added that he will address the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Special Session on Disarmament in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> next month and planned trips to <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. `` We can state confidently that we will last because we strive and struggle for peace,'' he said. `` Our opponents offer the <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> people war, and the people hate this.'' Also at a news conference Saturday, the head of the Soviet military contingent in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> said the anti-Communist rebels were taking their toll on the Soviet and Afghan troops but that rebel attacks will not deter the withdrawal, which begins Sunday. `` The opposition may have some effect on us, but not much, and certainly they will not be able to frustrate the timetable,'' Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON> told reporters. `` We have the means at our disposal to fulfill the timetable.'' The comments by <PERSON> Gromov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and the report of the rocket attack were carried in a <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> news agency pool report from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The Associated Press was excluded from the pool because of questions it asked Afghan President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> last month. Under an accord signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on April 14, the Soviets will complete their withdrawal within nine months. Half of the Soviets must be out by Aug. 15, according to the peace agreement. Soviet soldiers entered the war in December 1979 to help the allied government fight off the insurgents, and about 115,000 remain here to back forces loyal to President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>.
