<HEAD>Major Railroads Sue Minnesota Over New Occupied Caboose Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten major railroads are suing <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> to challenge a new state law requiring an occupied caboose on freight trains of a certain length carrying hazardous materials. The suit, filed Friday in federal court, contends that the law, which goes into effect Aug. 1, is pre-empted by <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> regulations that allow freight trains to operate in interstate commerce without occupied cabooses. The railroads also say federal law governing the efficient interstate transportation of hazardous materials pre-empts the caboose law. They say the new law discriminates against interstate transportation because it exempts certain local runs carrying such commodities as grain. Among the railroads seeking to have the federal court void the state law are <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION>, the Soo Line, <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Missabe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Iron Range Railway. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s new law states that trains more than 2,000 feet long that have cars marked as carrying hazardous materials must have a caboose at the end of the train and it must be occupied by at least one train crew member. Violations of the law would permit the state attorney general's office or a county sheriff to seek a civil penalty against the offending railroad The stated purpose of the law, which was pushed by railroad labor unions, was to promote rail safety by helping to spot equipment failure or problems with track beds. But opponents said it was merely an attempt by the railroad unions to preserve jobs no longer needed. `` A caboose is just no longer needed,'' <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiegold </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Burlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION>, said Saturday. He said there are computerized trackside monitors that indicate problems. Money also is a factor in dropping the caboose, <PERSON> Wiegold </PERSON> said. `` It's costly to keep those cabooses on there.''
