</LOCATION> charges $ 50 for a wedding license but does not require any test for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> charges $ 15 for a license, but it also requires a blood test for AIDS and syphilis, which can cost between $ 20 and $ 120 a person, depending on the laboratory. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Kenosha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Twins </ORGANIZATION>, said he thought of the mass wedding after watching county clerk <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Principe </PERSON> discuss on a news show the sudden rush of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> couples applying for <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> marriage licenses. `` If you look at baseball, it's a tradition. And marriage, well it's a tradition also, so it makes sense to have it here,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. `` I'm sure these wedding couples will remember this for a long time to come.'' <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Harter </PERSON>, an infielder for the <ORGANIZATION> Twins </ORGANIZATION>, said the ceremony was enjoyable, `` but I think we're all wondering who would get married on a baseball diamond. Maybe the real question is n't whether ` I do,' but ` Why here?''' Team officials said 14 couples registered for the wedding, and all but one showed up. The missing couple was from <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. The couples ranged in age from early 20s to late 50s. <PERSON> Corinne </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON>, 47, and <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, 56, both of <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said the wedding ceremony was the first time they had ever been on a baseball field.
