<HEAD>Voters Considering Whether To Shut Controversial Nuclear Power
Plant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 6 grafs after 5th graf, `In addition...', to add
quotes from both sides and from official on possible influence of
vote elsewhere. Picks up 6th graf, `The plant...' INSERTS one graf
after 9th graf pvs `The agency' with detail on 1985 incident. Trims
background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters here may become the first in the nation to shut down an operating nuclear power plant when they consider rival ballot measures to decide the fate of the problem-plagued Rancho Seco plant. A measure sponsored by a group called SAFE, or Sacramentans for Safe Energy, would order the permanent closure of the 14-year-old plant, one of the few publicly owned nuclear power plants in the country. An alternative plan put on the June 7 ballot by the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, which owns <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>, in effect asks the district's voters to give the the plant 25 miles southeast of here another chance. The utility district, which comprises <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> and surrounding areas with a combined population of more than 420,000, has struggled with operating problems at the plant for years. In addition, district consumers have struggled with electricity rates that have gone up nearly 85 percent in three years, and critics blame <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> for that, too. `` The thing has such a history of running so poorly and being unsafe that no one would believe it wo n't do the same thing in the future,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulholland </PERSON>, political director of <LOCATION> Campaign </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, an environmental and consumer's group working on the shutdown effort. `` We figure that the odds of Rancho Seco operating above the industry average are about the same as winning the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lottery,'' said <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Ory </PERSON> of Campaign <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Rancho Seco managers say the plant deserves another chance. `` We're champing at the bit to show the public we can do it,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Redeker </PERSON>, deputy operations manager. `` For the first time, we have an attitude of do it right.'' <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Smeloff </PERSON>, the only one of the five utility district board members who wants to shut down <ORGANIZATION> Rancho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seco </ORGANIZATION>, said passage of the measure could indirectly influence the private utilities that own the vast majority of the nation's nuclear plants. Even though those utilities are not under the control of the voters, as the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> utility is, they are sensitive to public opinion, he said. `` It certainly does, I think, set a tone if a local electorate does n't want a nuclear plant,'' he said. `` It would worry other utilities across the country even if the electorate does n't have the final say.'' The plant, built for $ 375 million by <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Wilcox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has a reactor design like that of Three Mile Island reactor No. 2, the site of the nation's worst commercial nuclear power plant accident in March 1979. From the day of its dedication in October 1974, the plant has been plagued by malfunctioning equipment and operator errors that forced more than 100 outages, including a shutdown that lasted from December 1985 to last month. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission called the overcooling accident that led to that shutdown one of the dozen worst problems suffered by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants in 1985. The agency gives the plant one of the worst efficiency ratings of any in the nation. Federal investigations have concluded that the plant had a history of mismanagement, poor or non-existent maintenance, poor operator training, inattention to detail, and failure to learn from past mistakes. A federal investigation of a 1985 overcooling accident also found that an important monitor was set at a level that would underestimate escaping radiation. Proponents of the shutdown, dubbed Measure B on the ballot, include Mayor <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudin </PERSON> and a majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. They argue that the plant will never be adequate or reliable and will require an endless stream of money for scheduled modifications and unforeseen repairs. Proponents of the alternate measure, Measure C, argue that the utility has spent $ 400 million to overhaul the plant, is hiring an outside company to manage it, and deserves a chance to prove <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>'s viability. But the proposed hiring of another manager has provoked another dispute because the company, <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, contributed $ 100,000 to the Measure C campaign. Measure C includes a provision that would call for the district to shut down Rancho Seco any time after Dec. 31 if the plant fails to operate at more than 50 percent of capacity for four consecutive months. In the past, the plant has managed to operate at an average of just 40 percent of capacity. The 50 percent requirement, however, could be overridden by four of the utility's five directors. Opponents of the plant question how legally binding Measure C would be. `` It's my legal opinion that Measure C in no way restricts the board from doing anything they want,'' said attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Remy </PERSON>, SAFE chairman. Whatever voters decide on June 7, the issue will almost certainly end up in court, <PERSON> Remy </PERSON> said.
