<HEAD>CDC Official Warns Educators Of Need For Prevention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The AIDS virus will reach epidemic proportions among young people, educators were told Saturday, unless a comprehensive prevention program on the disease is implemented in every school, at every grade level. Health officials at the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> believe adolescents experimenting with sex and drugs seriously risk contracting the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus, said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolsman </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s director of health promotion and education. `` We ca n't think -LRB- AIDS prevention -RRB- can be carried out through a pamphlet or a 15-minute lecture,'' <PERSON> Tolsman </PERSON> told an audience of more than 100 educators attending a conference on AIDS and education. `` We need a comprehensive program taught in health education classes by trained health education personnel to fight this problem,'' he said. `` We need your help to make sure adolescents understand what AIDS is and how it is prevented.'' <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> officials teamed with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to sponsor the three-day conference, which concludes Sunday. Educators received guidelines for educating students about AIDS and discussed AIDS infection among teenagers. The guidelines propose efforts at all grade levels, including early elementary school programs that reduce fears of an epidemic and teach students that the disease is not spread through casual contact. Late elementary and middle school programs should inform students about the disease itself, and junior and senior high school students should be told of the risks of contracting AIDS through sex or intravenous drug use, say the guidelines. Some educators expressed reservations about the plan. `` School health