<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did n't win <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s first-in-the-nation caucuses last February, did n't even come in second But now that he's the likely nominee, slightly embarrassed <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> Democrats are falling in line behind the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor. Not the least on their minds is 1992, and the prospect of losing the status of putting the first mark on the primary season. `` That's a key factor,'' said <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> party chairwoman <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, who admits her endorsement of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> last week was partly designed to curry favor with him in hopes he'll look kindly on <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> in 1992. `` Naturally, I give great thought to that.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> came in third in the Feb. 8 caucuses, behind winner <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> and runner-up <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>. But Missouri Rep. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> dropped out of the presidential race March 28 and <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, the senator from <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, suspended his campaign on April 7, leaving <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to battle for the nomination. About 3,000 Democratic activists were trooping to congressional district conventions Saturday to begin picking a slate of delegates that will bear only a passing resemblance to the much-ballyhooed outcome of the precinct caucuses. At those meetinngs, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> claimed 12 of the delegates elected, while <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> forces won nine technically uncommitted delegates, most of whom are expected to endorse <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> during the next month. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> claimed seven delegates, while <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> was awarded six. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s backers had hoped to maintain the