<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> arrived Saturday evening in poor, terrorism-plagued <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and heard a plea from President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> to reach out to `` those who are sick with hate and who kill and destroy with violence.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, on a 12-day, four-nation mission to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, arrived from neighboring <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> on an antiquated Aeroperu DC-8 jet. At <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s airport he expressed his sympathy with `` the huge multitude that has experienced grief, violence, abandonment and hunger'' in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. Later Saturday evening, scattered blackouts attributed to leftist sabotage hit <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> while the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was addressing priests, nuns and seminary students but did not affect the downtown area surrounding the colonial-era cathedral where he was. Outside the cathedral in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s central plaza the pope consecrated a Peruvian version of the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>. Tens of thousands of people cheered, waved white handkerchiefs and shouted, `` Viva,'' Spanish for `` long life.'' Then the pontiff retired for the night in the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. Small dynamite charges exploded in at least four spots in the city during Saturday night's papal activities, but police said no one was hurt. Authorities attributed the blasts to insurgents. Earlier in the day about 20 women disrupted a Mass in a Roman Catholic church in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, the capital, and appealed in the pope's name for respect for the rights of leftist rebels held in local prisons Guerrillas in a mountain town ambushed an army convoy and killed three soldiers. A military intelligence officer, who spoke to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on condition of anonymity, said two men posing as police with automatic rifles were arrested on the papal motorcade route from the <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> airport to downtown. He said there was an order to shoot and kill any armed suspect near the pope. Echoing a theme he stressed before in <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> cited <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s `` hunger for bread'' and called on its citizens to build `` a more fraternal and just society.'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, a nationalistic social reformer who has halted virtually all payment of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s $ 14.6 billion foreign debt, demanded a fairer shake for poor nations of the Third World. `` We reject the usurious terms of the foreign debt,'' the president told <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> at the airport. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, left the tropical Bolivian city of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> earlier Saturday. `` Do n't go away, holy father. Do n't leave us,'' Bolivian vice president <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayllon </PERSON> told the pope during a farewell ceremony, repeating a chant heard throughout the pontiff's five-day Bolivian stay. Addressing a Mass on Saturday in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> basin city of <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> insisted that `` constant, intense, honest and efficient work by everyone'' was needed to overcome poverty. `` We ca n't expect everything from outside.'' It has been three years since the pope has been to <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, a country bloodied by an unrelenting leftist insurgency. When he was here in 1985 he pleaded with rebels to abandon their armed struggle to overthrow <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s elected government. But the violence is worse than ever and the country is submerged in a serious economic crisis. Inflation expected to top a record 400 percent this year year and the country has virtually no dollars left in reserves to maintain imports and economic growth. On Sunday the pope planned to celebrate an open air Mass, meet with church officials and business and cultural leaders and close a conference of Latin American bishops. Monday he continues on to <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>, his last stop. Police said the women who occupied the church Saturday surrounded a priest saying Mass and held a large banner reading: `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, intercede for our brothers, political prisoners.'' Witnesses said police took the protesters away in vans. Police confirmed the incident but said they had no information on arrests. The women identified themselves as relatives of prisoners accused of belonging to the pro-Cuba <ORGANIZATION> Tupac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amaru </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, a small rebel band active since 1984. The government President <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, who took office in 1985, is also plagued by the fanatical Mao-inspired <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION>, which launched its insurgency in May 1980. Shining Path guerrillas Saturday ambushed an army convoy near the <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Huancasancos </LOCATION>, killing three soldiers wounding three others, the military said in a communique. More than 10,000 people have died in the violence since 1980, including rebels, policemen, soldiers, public officials and civilians. More than half of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s population of 21 million people live under states of emergencies in different parts of the country.
