 bleak. `` <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> comes each time with the same plan _ the original plan a little more elastic. It is a deadline for -LRB- <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> -RRB- resigning his post, a deadline for leaving the country.'' he said. `` It is a plan that the general and the Panamanian republic can not accept.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> told reporters: `` The experiment of -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- aggression that exists in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is a testing ground that later could be applied to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> or any country.'' The general faces other pressures, however, beyond those from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The country's economy is collapsing under the strain of the crisis. A team of five respected economists published a study this week saying production was half of normal because of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sanctions and banking restrictions. They said more than a quarter of the work force will be unemployed within months, even if the political crisis were resolved tomorrow. They raised the specter of hunger and said it would take at least two years of intensive recovery measures and massive international aid to get the economy back to a semblance of what it was a year ago. They said recovery can not even begin until the political crisis stemming from <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s hold on power is settled. But that appears further off with each passing day. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, is one of the few opposition leaders who has not gone underground or into exile. He said Thursday that, though there are no more anti-government street demonstrations and other protest has been quashed, `` The crisis has deepened in that socie