<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters here may become the first in the nation to shut down an operating nuclear power plant when they consider rival ballot measures to decide the fate of the problem-plagued Rancho Seco plant. A measure sponsored by a group called SAFE, or Sacramentans for Safe Energy, would order the permanent closure of the 14-year-old plant, one of the few publicly owned nuclear power plants in the country. An alternative plan put on the June 7 ballot by the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, which owns <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION>, in effect asks the district's voters to give the the plant 25 miles southeast of here another chance.
