<TEXT>
 After a four-year study on new technologies, the government has concluded that the next two decades will be a time of massive change in which virtually every <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> product, service and job will be reshaped. The study, done by the <ORGANIZATION> congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> and released on Saturday, said that Americans in the 21st century should enjoy longer, more productive lives than any preceding generation. The study said that emerging technologies should offer the opportunity to expand educational opportunities, extend life and reduce sickness and make work more rewarding by using machines for tedious, repetitive jobs.
