<HEAD>War-Torn Sri Lanka Makes Great Locale for Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Indiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> sought the <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doom </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, he was really doing it in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Likewise, when <PERSON> Tarzan </PERSON> romped through the jungle he was not in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> but near the Sri Lankan hill town of <LOCATION> Kandy </LOCATION>. The late filmmaker Sir <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> once referred to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> as `` the most natural and complete outdoor set,'' and this island nation, despite its long war by Tamil militants for a separate homeland, continues to lure <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and British moviemakers. The fight by Tamil guerrillas for an independent nation for their minority people broke out in 1983. The Tamils, who are 18 percent of the island's 16 million people, claim they are discriminated against by the majority <PERSON> Sinhalese </PERSON>. Since 1980, at least seven major films have been produced around the lush mountains, dense jungles, rivers and waterfalls near <LOCATION> Kandy </LOCATION>, barely a three-hour drive into the hills from the capital of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Villages near <LOCATION> Kandy </LOCATION>, once the capital of a <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> kingdom, have been villages everywhere from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in various movies. `` <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> has managed to cheat as countries like <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Asoka </PERSON> <PERSON> Perera </PERSON>, managing director of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> Film Locations Limited. <PERSON> Perera </PERSON>'s company helps scout locations for movies, and he said <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s success in drawing filmmakers is due to a lack of red tape involved in shooting here. One of the first major movies made in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> was in 1956 when director <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lean </PERSON> filmed his hit movie `` Bridge on the River Kwai'' on the island, then known as <ORGANIZATION> Ceylon </ORGANIZATION>. The film about British POWs in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> who are forced to build a bridge for the Japanese during World War II, won six Academy Awards. The movie was set partly here, so when <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON> escaped a Japanese prison on <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and made his way through fierce jungle and across sun-baked seas to a British base on <ORGANIZATION> Ceylon </ORGANIZATION>, he was really just around the corner from where he started. Paramount's `` The Purple Plain'' with <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>, also about the <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> campaign during World War II, and `` Elephant Walk'' starring <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> in a movie about a <ORGANIZATION> Ceylon </ORGANIZATION> tea plantation, were both made in 1954. But <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> lost out as a location for foreign movies from 1970-77 when the pro-socialist government led by the <ORGANIZATION> Sri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lankan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> viewed anything coming from the West as decadent. It was not until 1980 that the trend was reversed when <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Derek </PERSON>'s `` Tarzan the Apeman'' was filmed starring his wife, <PERSON> Bo </PERSON> <PERSON> Derek </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. Since then, movies shot in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> have included the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas-Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> `` <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jones </LOCATION> and the Temple of Doom''; `` Mountbatten _ the Last Viceroy''; `` Light Over the Water,'' which was set partly in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>; `` Further Adventures of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Buck,'' in which <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> masquerades as <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>; and `` Jungle Heat,'' in which the country plays itself. `` Iron Triangle,'' about an American troop operation in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, completed production here in February and is to be released later this year. It stars Beau Bridges and <PERSON> Haing </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ngor </PERSON>, who won an Academy Award for supporting actor in <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Joffe </PERSON>'s critically acclaimed `` The Killing Fields.'' <PERSON> Jayantha </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayatillaka </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> Film Locations Limited, said films made here earn the country needed foreign exchange and give a boost to the tourist industry. Expenditures on filming in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> were reported to be $ 8 million for `` <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION>,'' $ 5 million for `` Tarzan the Apeman'' and $ 3 million for `` Iron Triangle. <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s mix of cultures also helps producers find `` extras'' for their projects, thus reducing their costs, <PERSON> Jayatillaka </PERSON> said. `` For the making of ` Iron Triangle,' Sri Lankans of Chinese descent and those who were descendants of traders from <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> were recruited to play Vietnamese,'' he said. But <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s ethnic conflict, born from that same cultural mix, has blocked filming on some parts of the island, <PERSON> Perera </PERSON> said. `` Some of the scenes of ` Tarzan the Apeman' were filmed at the beaches in eastern <LOCATION> Trincomalee </LOCATION> district in 1980 before the violence broke out,'' he said. `` Since 1983, we have to stay clear of the north and east despite the fact there are some beautiful locations there.'' But <PERSON> Perera </PERSON> said spectacular scenery and miles of palm-lined beaches exist elsewhere on the island. The island is being considered for a movie about a journalist in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> during the overthrow of President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. The movie's star, <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilling </PERSON> of the Australian TV series `` Return to Eden,'' was recently in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> with producer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Markowitz </PERSON>. Keeping with the international spirit of moviemaking here, the production is being handled by an Australian company.
