<HEAD>Repairs Continue at Prison Scarred by Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Prison Riots-Aftermath</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 These days, a visitor can drive directly through wide-open iron gates and park within 20 yards of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penitentiary </ORGANIZATION>'s front steps. Those are the same steps descended by 89 hostages when they poured out of the prison last Dec. 4, ending an 11-day uprising by more than 1,100 Cuban inmates. The penitentiary then was less a prison than a badly damaged fortress under siege. The front steps, patrolled constantly by armed federal officers, led to a building only partly controlled by authorities. The rest was in the hands of Cuban detainees, who rioted at word of a deportation agreement with <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>. When it was all over, the prison was emptied of all inmates for the first time since it opened in 1902 and officials began cleaning up the damage. Officials estimated the damage here and in <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, where Cuban inmates staged a similar uprising, at $ 64 million. Now, 600 inmates, all Americans, are housed at the prison, compared with about 200 Americans and 1,400 Cuban inmates at the time of the takeover. In two years, the number is to reach 800 to 850. So far, there are no plans to bring Cuban detainees to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Caltabiano </PERSON>, executive assistant to Warden <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON>. The riot interrupted a $ 63 million, five-year renovation project, but many of the areas damaged were to be razed in the renovation anyway, <PERSON> Caltabiano </PERSON> said. The only real loss, he said, was the burned-out prison industries building. A temporary industries unit has been set up in a former gymnasium. There, inmates repairing mailbags and making mattresses and meteorological parachutes earned $ 500,000 for the prison in April, <PERSON> Caltabiano </PERSON> said. A 20-foot-high chain link fence is being erected to cut the prison almost in half. Behind it, most of the construction will go on. The first phase of the renovation project is to be completed next year. Elsewhere, vandalism in the dining hall and chapel has been repaired. `` It's been the positive attitude of the staff that's made it, by putting this kind of thing behind them and saying, ` OK, we're going to see how we can rebuild <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>,''' <PERSON> Caltabiano </PERSON> said The prison is `` <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'' or `` USP -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Penitentiary -RRB- <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'' to its employees. It was known as the `` Big A'' to decades of inmates, including the famous and the infamous. At the dawn of the 1920s, the `` Big A'' was home to Socialist presidential candidate <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Debs </PERSON>, who was imprisoned for a speech condemning war in World War I. It held <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> in the 1930s, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> spy <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Able </PERSON> in the 1950s and Mafia informant <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Valachi </PERSON> in the 1960s. In the late 1970s, there were 16 slayings at the prison, many described as professional `` hits'' related to drug sales. By 1978, a report by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> suggested closing the penitentiary because its old design and deteriorating structures made security impossible. The prison was to have been closed by the fall of 1984. But the number of Cuban inmates, detained during the Mariel boatlift because of their records in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> or imprisoned later for offenses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, mounted. Violence again was a problem. The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> reported the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> pen had less than 10 percent of all federal prisoners, but almost 20 percent of all assaults on inmates or guards. The Cubans frequently protested prison conditions but more often complained that they were being detained at all. The final uprising was triggered by word that deportations to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> would resume.
