<HEAD>The Right To Write: Should Regan Have Kissed And Told?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was talking last week about two things: what <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said and whether he should have said it. Beyond the spate of jokes produced by his revelations about Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s fascination with astrology and the president's passive management style, there arose a debate over the ethics of kiss-and-tell books. `` If you want to contribute to history, it wo n't hurt to wait until the administration is over,'' said <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s former spokeswoman But <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON>, former press secretary to President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, said administration figures should be able to tell their stories whenever they wish. `` Speech in this country is free,'' says <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON>, who teaches journalism ethics at <ORGANIZATION> Marquette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` Unless those people had agreed that they would not do anything like this, I ca n't see it as being unethical.'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s book, `` For the Record: From Wall Street to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' is a biting account that some feel weakens an already lame-duck presidency. He portrays a choeographed president, manipulated by aides and by a wife who depends on an astrologist for guidance in fixing the president's schedule. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has denounced the book as `` a bunch of falsehoods'' and a `` breach of confidence'' but not given a detailed rebuttal. Being kissed by the heady power of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and then publicly telling the story, especially when the president still sits in the Oval Office, is to some dishonorable, to others a valuable contribution to history. The president's former chief of staff, ousted from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> last year in a move widely believed engineered by Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, says he never considered delaying his tale. `` I did n't set the time of my leaving this administration and I do n't know why I should hold up ... Many people have left this administration and told their stories. Why not my book?'' he said in an interview. His is one of several negative accounts by former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> officials. Former White House spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> offered damaging characterizations of former colleagues in his book, `` Speaking Out.'' He says he may have overstepped `` the bounds of propriety in some instances'' but addes: `` I apologize not for the truth in my book _ nor the telling of it.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s former budget director, caused a furor two years ago with `` The Triumph of Politics: Why the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Revolution Failed,'' which lays out errors in judgment and miscalculations <PERSON> Stockman </PERSON> says were responsible for adding $ 1 trillion to the national debt. `` I wrote the book because I have an ax to grind,'' he said then, and to correct `` a gigantic mishap of governance.'' Ironically, one of those who warned <PERSON> Stockman </PERSON> against being too candid was <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, then treasury secretary. Just why the Reagan-era books have been so angry and revealing is a provocative question. <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON> says he has never encountered books `` as violent'' as those spawned by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency and adds: `` There is obviously something in that White House that is filling people with a sense of rage.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, the first lady's former spokeswoman, dismisses that theory. `` This is not a problem peculiar to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration,'' she says. `` There's big money being offered and staff have become more powerful. It's the cult of the personality. A lot of people who worked in the White House in the'50s were nameless and faceless. In the'80s they have high-profile jobs that bring a lot of personal attention to them.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Barber </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> political science professor who studies presidential character, notes that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> books have a `` remarkable consistency in the picture they convey of this White House.'' `` Where is the book that overwhelmingly corrects these supposedly false and unjust smear jobs ... that straightens it all out, that shows that the president was really in charge?'' he asks. He believes such books help citizens learn how policymakers do their jobs and whether their `` values are right.'' That thought is echoed by historian <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who says these memoirs are a `` venerable genre in <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> political literature'' that should not be withheld. `` How else can history be written if those who make it take vows of silence?'' he said. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kernell </PERSON>, a political science professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> who is studying the White House staff, says the proliferation of such books reflects `` the growth of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the centralization of power'' in unknown people making vital decisions. He notes that the White House staff has grown from about 40 people in 1939 to nearly 500 today. Those people `` have tremendous influence on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> policy. So we're naturally curious about them. That's why they get on the cover of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> and why their books are marketable.'' On the other hand, telling how an administration operates while it is still operating can put a damper on administration programs. `` The proposition that there even are going to be kiss-and-tell books does erode the sense of collegiality within government,'' says <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> scholar who served on the <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> staffs and has studied the presidency and the press. `` If you sit there at a table and you know that everybody is going to run back and write in their diary, it will affect what you can say and how you say it,'' <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> says. `` It becomes simply an ethical consideration, based on each person's moral code, whether they're going to tell tales out of school. It tells you something about those people.'' Some have suggested presidents ask incoming aides to sign a promise not to write until later. `` What ever happened to the First Amendment?'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> says in response. `` Do n't we have as much right to write? I could see if that applied to state secrets. But I do n't describe how to make an atomic bomb.'' <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s press secretary who wrote a book targeting the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> press corps, says he promised his administration colleagues `` they were n't ever going to have to see their top-of-the-head statements and analyses tossed back at them years later'' in one of his books. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> says the promise was his idea and was not put into any formal agreement. Many feel such agreements, probably unforceable in any case, would only underscore an atmosphere of distrust. There may always be people who put loyalty to the president behind the prospect of financial gain, celebrity status or avenging some real or imagined slight. `` Presidents get what they deserve. They either generate a sense of loyalty among the members of their staff or they do n't,'' says <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> bristles at the notion that he has been disloyal and recalls how he was `` hounded out of my office.'' Loyalty, he says, is a two-way proposition. In the end, says <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, `` I could either write this book and tell the whole truth or not write the book at all. I chose to write the book.''
</TEXT>
