<FIRST>d f PM-EconomyRdp     05-14 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Fueled Moderate Boost in Wholesale Prices in April</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A moderate rise in wholesale prices during April despite a big jump in energy prices has prompted economists to conclude that inflation worries may have been overstated. The Producer Price Index rose a moderate 0.4 percent in April, down from a 0.6 percent advance in March, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. Analysts noted that if the volatile energy and food sectors were removed, the April price advance was a minuscule 0.1 percent. `` It is hard to make a real scare story that inflation is taking off based on these kinds of numbers,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. For the first four months of the year, wholesale prices have risen at an annual rate of 2.9 percent, not much changed from the 2.2 percent increase for all of 1987 The report sparked a rally in the bond markets as investors concluded there will be no additional pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to drive interest rates higher to dampen demand. Prices of long-term government bonds rose as much as $ 5 for each $ 1,000 in face value to yield 9.17 percent. On Thursday the bellwether 30-year issue's yield jumped to its highest point this year at 9.22 percent. Other economists, however, insisted that the April price report contained some troubling signs that price increases will be accelerating in the months ahead. `` It would be a mistake to look at this report and say inflationary pressures have abated,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, head of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> forecasting firm. `` I do n't think this relief is going to last.'' Energy prices, which had posted sharp declines from September through February, accounted for half of the increase in the overall index in April, rising 3.1 percent. Gasoline costs advanced 0.7 percent, while home heating oil shot up 5.2 percent. Natural gas, which had declined in price in five of the last six months, rose 4.3 percent. Food costs rose 0.4 percent in April as a sharp 16.3 percent drop in the price of eggs and smaller declines in the price of fruit, fish and beef offset price increases for pork, chicken, vegetables and coffee. The financial markets took the economic news in stride. On Wall Street, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average climbed 22.55 points to close at 1,990.55. Brokers noted that there were no unpleasant surprises in the producer price index and instead drew inspiration from falling interest rates and a steady dollar. In another economic report Friday, the government said total business sales surged 1.9 percent in March, the biggest advance in more than a year, while business inventories were up a modest 0.3 percent. Analysts said the combination of rising sales and small declines in inventories should translate into continued strong industrial production in the months ahead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>